<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Finance loophole advisers attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VENICE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Accountants and lawyers have been actively involved in avoiding financial
reporting regulations, an academic told the European Accounting Association
annual conference in Venice yesterday.
The involvement of lawyers, auditors and corporate financiers in developing
capital instruments had undermined rule-based regulations, Mr Atul Shah, of
the University of Bristol, said.
In a case study of convertible capital bonds he said the instrument was
designed to exploit tax and accounting loopholes. He said rule-based
regulation was 'doomed to failure' because professionals actively helped
their clients to evade these rules. He quoted advertisements and articles in
trade journals which he said were marketing initiatives by lawyers selling
avoidance schemes.
He also cited interviews conducted with bankers saying that they could not
have designed and implemented these schemes without close co-operation from
lawyers and auditors.
Mr Shah said no single professional was involved in packaging the whole
avoidance scheme, suggesting that ethical considerations did not limit their
actions.
</TEXT>
