<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Brown sets out high-skill vision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain needs to become a fairer society if economic efficiency is to be
significantly improved, Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, will argue
today.
Mr Brown will use a Fabian Society lecture to set out a vision of a highly
skilled Britain in which all forms of privilege and discrimination have been
removed.
Building on remarks before last month's jobs summit of the Group of Seven
leading industrial nations in Detroit, the shadow chancellor will argue that
enhancing the value of labour is the key to Britain's future prosperity.
This would require a programme of investment and training, including the
creation of a university for industry modelled on the Open University. This
should be accompanied by policies to reduce unemployment and reform the
welfare system to ensure that it is geared to the modern labour market,
rather than the one of 1945.
Mr Brown will argue that the casualisation of the labour market over the
past 15 years has produced a situation in which the root causes of
unfairness in society are increasingly work-related. The government has
falsely equated de-regulation with flexibility. Better regulation and not
necessarily less regulation is what is needed.
</TEXT>
