<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Pounds 50m revamp for Selfridges store
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sears, the retailing group, is planning to spend Pounds 50m over three years
on its Selfridges department store in London's Oxford Street.
The investment is on top of Pounds 12.6m spent last year on creating a new
escalator well from the basement to the fourth floor at the store's eastern
end, and Pounds 2.5m on new electronic sales terminals. That means total
investment will be Pounds 65m in four years.
Mr Liam Strong, Sears' chief executive, said the programme was an investment
in the Selfridges brand. He is confident of earning a return.
The 450,000 sq ft store has some of the highest sales densities in Europe in
its ground floor cosmetics departments. But average sales per sq ft, at
between Pounds 400 and Pounds 500 a year, are low compared to other Oxford
Street stores.
One problem is that behind the grandiose front is an irregularly shaped
building with a mass of columns obscuring eyelines. Customers do not
circulate properly.
Mr Tim Daniels, Selfridges' managing director, says research found that only
4 per cent to 5 per cent of shoppers ever visited the fourth floor.
To improve customer flows, more than half of the Pounds 50m will be spent on
structural changes.
In addition the haphazard layout, with related products often scattered
around six selling floors, will be rationalised.
</TEXT>
