<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Ukraine election declared valid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JILL BARSHAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ukraine's first post-Soviet parliamentary elections were declared valid
yesterday as fears of voter apathy proved unfounded.
As Ukrainians flocked to polling booths, preliminary turnout returns showed
that voting surpassed the 50 per cent threshold to make the election valid
in more than 310 of the 350 constituencies which held a final-stage ballot
yesterday. Ninety MPs had already been elected in previous rounds for the
450-seat legislative body which began on March 27.
Although about 75 per cent of the electorate voted in the first round, voter
turnout was an important issue in the campaign.
President Leonid Kravchuk's aides predicted that voter apathy would elect
less than a quorum of 300 MPs and enable Mr Kravchuk to establish direct
presidential rule.
'A parliament will be formed,' said Mr Ivan Yemetz, chairman of the Central
Electoral Commission, on television last night.
Although results were not expected until today, the parliament's composition
is likely to be divided between Moscow-leaning communists and allies and
western-oriented nationalists, along with an equally large group of
independents.
Casting his ballot yesterday morning, Mr Kravchuk reiterated his intention
to delay presidential elections, scheduled for June, until the new
parliament defined presidential powers.
Throughout the capital, Kiev, voter turnout fell short of the 50 per cent
threshold despite the closing-hour extensions granted to polling stations.
Only eight of its 21 constituencies elected MPs.
Contrary to expectations, the independence-seeking region of Crimea and its
Russian-dominated Black Sea fleet base of Sevastopol elected all but one of
its 23 MPs to the Kiev parliament.
</TEXT>
