<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Israel defiant over territories' closure: Cabinet approves
permits for 18,000 foreigners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel prepared for a prolonged closure of the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip yesterday, in spite of warnings from some of its ministers that it
would impoverish Palestinians, harm Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and fuel
violence in the territories.
The cabinet agreed to grant new work permits for 18,000 foreign workers to
be substitutes for Palestinian labourers banned from crossing into Israel,
suggesting that the government is preparing for a extended closure of the
occupied territories.
The closure, to be reviewed by the cabinet next week, has serious
implications for the already low standards of living of hundreds of
thousands of Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip who are dependent
on income from jobs in Israel.
By increasing Israel's trend towards independence and separation from the
territories, the measure could also have negative implications for the
long-term prospects of the Palestinian economy and for Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks which resumed in Cairo yesterday.
Gen Matan Vilnai, army chief of the southern command, said the maintenance
of a rigid closure policy, which has barred up to 70,000 Palestinians from
travelling to their jobs in Israel, would provoke an upsurge in violence in
the West Bank and Gaza. The territories were sealed on Thursday after
extremist Islamic guerrillas killed eight Israelis.
Cabinet ministers said the government was determined to maintain a lengthy
closure to prevent Palestinians from making further attacks against
Israelis. Although the cabinet agreed to review the closure at next Sunday's
meeting, Mr Yacov Tzur, minister of agriculture, said a full closure would
last until the Jewish holiday of Rosh Hashana in September 'to free
ourselves from the dependence of Palestinians which endangers our security'.
Left-wing cabinet ministers warned that a lengthy closure would impose
tremendous suffering on the Palestinians and called for the immediate
injection of increased aid into the territories to alleviate poverty. Mr
Yair Tsaban, minister of absorption, feared the closure could harm peace
talks and make it impossible for Mr Yassir Arafat, PLO chairman, to take
over the Gaza Strip and West Bank town of Jericho under the Palestinian
self-rule agreement currently being hammered out in Cairo.
The cabinet move came hours before Israel and the PLO resumed talks in Cairo
amid increasing Palestinian frustration and signs that it is now almost
impossible for the two sides to reach final agreement before the April 13
deadline.
</TEXT>
