<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Nato's air onslaught risks alienating diplomatic ally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
By using one of the most powerful military weapons at its disposal - air
power - the west has run the risk of throwing away one of its most powerful
diplomatic weapons: a united front at the UN Security Council.
The Nato air strikes will test to the very limit the common front between
the west and Russia, which has transformed international diplomacy and given
new teeth to the United Nations since the collapse of the Soviet Union.
As one of the Security Council's permanent members, Russia is a party to all
the resolutions which the west has invoked in justification of its action
against the Bosnian Serbs.
But Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister who represents the most
liberal and pro-western part of the country's political spectrum, has often
called into question whether these resolutions give Nato absolute freedom to
launch attacks.
Yesterday's action will echo loudly in Russia, where any sign that Moscow is
cast in the role of lapdog to the west will provide the hardline opposition
with a new stick with which to beat President Boris Yeltsin.
In recent months western officials have been astonished by the trenchancy
with which Russia has demarcated its perceived interests across a whole
range of foreign policy issues: from respect for the rights of
Russian-speakers abroad to the question of access to foreign markets for its
arms industry.
The US was surprised and initially dismayed by the firmness and skill of
Russian diplomacy in February, when Moscow simultaneously protected and
reined in its traditional allies by sending peacekeepers to the Serb sector
of Sarajevo.
Paradoxically enough, the resurgence of the old adversarial relationship
between the 'superpowers' - with each side having clearly defined interests
 -brought a new dynamism to the Bosnian peacekeeping effort.
Mr Charles Redman and Mr Vitaly Churkin, the envoys of Washington and Moscow
respectively, established a close working relationship that paved the way
for a ground-breaking deal between Croats and Moslems on establishing a
federation.
But the involvement of the US and Russia on opposite sides has also raised
the stakes in the conflict.
In a state of affairs that is all too reminiscent of the cold war period,
the Bosnian war is now a 'regional conflict' whose status unavoidably
affects the wider relationship between the great powers.
If the Yeltsin administration feels politically secure enough to make a cool
judgment of its own strategic interests, it will not turn Bosnia into a
make-or-break issue in its relations with the west.
As some Russian nationalists will grudgingly concede, Moscow has far more at
stake in managing its relations with Germany - the traditional friend of the
Croats - than in shoring up, at any cost, a friendship with a small and
unpredictable ally.
A heavy-handed intervention in support of the Serbs and against the Moslems
could also threaten the internal stability of Russia, which has at least 10m
Moslem citizens of its own - from the independence-minded enclave of
Tatarstan to the warrior nations of the northern Caucasus.
However, opposition to the idea of punitive action against the Serbs runs
across a wide political spectrum in Russia, and all factions in the Russian
parliament can now be expected to redouble their campaign to end the
country's participation in sanctions against Belgrade.
Friendship with Serbia is a rallying cry for old-guard communists, for the
maverick nationalist Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky and for traditional Russian
patriots who recall their country's role in liberating the Serbs from
Ottoman rule in the 19th century.
The wilder fringes of Serb nationalism provoke almost as much exasperation
in Moscow as they do in the west. But Russia, in its newly self-confident
form, cannot expose itself to the risk of diplomatic humiliation.
In February, Russia was able, by some subtle diplomatic footwork, to raise
its profile in Bosnia and score a diplomatic triumph, at the very time when
the Serbian cause looked doomed to a humiliating reverse.
Even more skill will be needed now to shore up Russian prestige, without
damaging its broader strategic interests or upsetting the country's internal
political balance.
</TEXT>
