<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / UN backs further raids to defend safe areas
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
United Nations secretary-general Boutros Boutros Ghali has given UN
peacekeepers 'carte blanche' to make further use of air power to protect
Bosnian safe areas, his spokeswoman said after the raids.
Mr Boutros Ghali's spokeswoman, Ms Therese Gastaut, said: 'The
secretary-general would like to make it very clear that he will not hesitate
to use close air support again to protect the UN-designated safe areas.'
The raids won swift endorsement from Nato governments as a way to further
efforts to find a comprehensive peace in Bosnia. However, the Bosnian
ambassador to the US said the raids were 'too little, too late' in response
to the sustained Serb attack on the Gorazde enclave. There was no official
reaction from Moscow, which has cautioned Nato strongly against enforcing UN
policy in Bosnia.
Ms Gastaut said the decision to ask Nato for air support had been taken by
Mr Yasushi Akashi - Mr Boutros Ghali's special representative in former
Yugoslavia and head of UN peacekeeping operations there - after
consultations earlier on Sunday with Mr Boutros Ghali.
Mr Muhamed Sacirbey, the Bosnian ambassador to the UN, told CNN news that
the attack was more of a message than a real response to the Serb advance on
Gorazde. He called for the Serb troops to be withdrawn to lines previously
agreed with the UN.
Mr Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian prime minister, acknowledged reports of a
direct hit on the headquarters of the Serbian troops attacking the town.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, was informed of the air strikes minutes
before they took place. Downing Street later said: 'This is the sort of
action that Nato always said might be necessary. It did not need his (Mr
Major's) approval since the actions have been sanctioned by UN resolutions.'
The German government spokesman, Mr Dieter Vogel, said Bonn hoped the air
strikes would advance the Bosnian peace process. He said: 'The attackers of
Gorazde have no one to blame but themselves for this answer from Nato.'
</TEXT>
