<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Nato air strike halts Serb shelling: US jets attack to
protect embattled Bosnian enclave - Clinton warns of tough resolve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nato aircraft attacked Serb forces advancing on the Moslem enclave of
Gorazde last night, the first time the alliance has acted on its
long-standing threat to use air power to protect Bosnian towns.
The United Nations said the air strike, aimed at an artillery command post,
succeeded in stopping the Serb shelling. But President Bill Clinton quickly
warned that Washington would support further air attacks on Serb positions
if requested by UN military commanders in Bosnia.
He said the raid by two US F-16 fighter bombers, based at Aviano in Italy,
was a clear signal of UN and US resolve. He urged the Serbs to roll back
their two-week-old offensive on Gorazde, one of three 'safe areas' for
Moslems in eastern Bosnia. At least 100 people have been killed and 400
wounded in the fighting around the enclave.
General Sir Michael Rose, the head of UN forces in Bosnia, said he had
called for the raid after a tank began firing into the centre of the town.
He said the shelling stopped 18 minutes after the aircraft dived out of a
rain cloud to drop their bombs.
According to Mr Michael Williams, the UN's chief spokesman in former
Yugoslavia, the action was taken under Security Council resolution 836,
which 'allows for the use of air power, in and around the safe areas, to
support Unprofor (the UN protection force) in the performance of its
mandate'.
He added that UN military observers and humanitarian personnel, as well as
Bosnian civilians, were at direct risk from the shelling, and that the
Bosnian Serb leadership had been warned of this yesterday afternoon.
He said General Bertrand de Lapresle, head of UN forces in former
Yugoslavia, hoped to meet the Bosnian Serb leader, Mr Radovan Karadzic, and
Bosnian Moslem President Alija Izetbegovic today. 'We would hope that the
peace process is not seriously impaired,' Mr Williams said.
However, Mr Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian prime minister, said the Moslems
would not join the talks unless the Serbs retreated to the positions they
occupied before the battle over Gorazde.
General Milan Gvero, deputy commander of the Bosnian Serb armed forces,
accused Nato of bombing civilian targets, and described the strikes as 'an
attack on Serbian civilisation', but did not threaten reprisals against Nato
or the UN.
However, the Nato action raises the possibility of a dispute with Russia,
where the Serb cause is strongly supported. According to the Yugoslav news
agency, the Serb army's Hercegovina Corps warned: 'By this act, Nato carried
out a clear act of aggression against Serb people, striking at civilian
targets far from the front line.'
Gen Rose has struggled unsuccessfully in recent days to arrange a ceasefire
in Gorazde in preparation for a longer-term truce. The Nato operation
followed reports of heavy artillery and small-arms fire reaching as far as
the centre of the enclave, home to 65,000 Moslems.
Mr Kris Janowski, a spokesman for the UN High Commission for Refugees, said
shortly before the air attack that thousands of desperate villagers were
pouring into Gorazde amid a heavy artillery barrage. 'People can see
villages around Gorazde burning and there is constant fire from howitzers in
and around the centre.' He added that the UNHCR building had come under
small-arms fire and people had been targeted by snipers.
The US involvement marks a turning point in the conflict. In recent days,
Pentagon officials had questioned whether air strikes would be effective in
ending the conflict over Gorazde, and played down the scale of the fighting.
However, the administration came under pressure to act as the UN reported an
intensification of the Serb assault and warned that the townspeople were
increasingly desperate.
Gen Rose told Reuter news agency he had warned Serb commanders three times
in telephone and fax messages they would be bloodied if they continued
advancing on Gorazde. 'We warned them very firmly that if this continues we
would have to resort to appropriate action and they knew exactly what we
meant,' he said.
The UNHCR, concerned about reprisals against its staff, said it would
suspend aid convoys through Serb-controlled territory.
Air onslaught risks alienating Russia, Page 3
</TEXT>
