<HEADLINE>
FT  11 APR 94 / Lift-truck maker Lancer Boss calls in the receivers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lancer Boss Group, one of the UK's biggest privately owned manufacturing
companies and the last big UK-owned producer of lift trucks, called in
receivers over the weekend.
The move was prompted by a disagreement between the company's German unit,
Steinbock Boss, and its German banks over expansion plans. The banks
withdrew their support for Steinbock, leaving the unit with no option but to
go into receivership.
Receivers were also called in to the protect the British companies, although
Lancer Boss is likely to continue operations if - as expected  - it is sold.
The move ends 37 years of control of Lancer Boss by the founding brothers
and owners, Sir Neville Bowman-Shaw and Mr Trevor Bowman-Shaw.
The probable sale of Lancer Boss is likely to generate intense interest
among rival lift-truck manufacturers and could herald a new round of
consolidation in the lift-truck industry.
Lancer Boss, based in Leighton Buzzard, Bedfordshire, has annual sales of
about Pounds 180m, 1,200 employees worldwide (including 700 in the UK) and
one of the widest and most modern product ranges in the industry.
Sir Neville yesterday said: 'I hope the group is welded back together again,
although it will be under new ownership.'
He said a receiver was appointed for Steinbock Boss after its banking group,
led by Bayerische Hypo-Bank, withdrew its support from the Moosburg-based
producer which Lancer Boss bought in 1983.
Later on Friday, in order to protect the British companies in the Lancer
Boss group, Sir Neville asked British banks led by NatWest to appoint a
receiver for several British subsidiaries. Mr Allan Griffiths of Grant
Thornton has been appointed receiver and, with a team of 20 people, has
spent most of the weekend at the company's offices in Leighton Buzzard.
Sir Neville is believed to have been planning to link up with a non-German
company, possibly Komatsu of Japan. However, the German banks may have
wanted Steinbock to link with Jungheinrich, the Hamburg-based lift-truck
producer, which is ranked third biggest in the world.
Lancer Boss had pre-tax profits of Pounds 4.7m on sales of Pounds 200m in
the year ended April 1993, but was expecting to report a big loss for the
following year.
Mr Griffiths said he had no doubts that Lancer Boss would be sold as a going
concern, but he still has to clarify the status of Steinbock Boss's
receivership.
Lancer Boss is expected to hold a press conference today to outline its
position.
Let-down for lift-truck, Page 8
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
