<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Arts: American songfest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When does a British orchestra sound like an American orchestra? Hardly ever
 -except when Leonard Slatkin conducts it; as he did the Philharmonia on
Wednesday in an all-American programme, the first of their three
contributions to the Festival of American Music on the South Bank.
An immensely professional conductor with a sharp ear, Slatkin knows exactly
how to obtain the sound he wants for this repertoire.
William Schuman's unadvertised American Festival Overture, expertly rackety
and hard-edged, made a rousing start, though it took the concert well beyond
its advertised length. Its title must be a homage to Brahms, whose Academic
Festival Overture was equally an unbuttoned exercise by a conservative
craftsman, not unlike Sir William Walton.
In fact, the Schuman rather shaded the Four Dance Episodes from Copland's
Rodeo. Though the final Hoe-Down is a Copland evergreen, his lively ideas in
the rest of the suite seem pasted together with routine crudity, as in most
ballet suites. Next week the Third Symphony should represent him better. In
Barber's Cello Concerto, Ralph Kirshbaum replaced the originally advertised
soloist - and very well, with much flair and feeling. It was not his fault
that Barber's romantic, sedulously neo-European idiom sounds more and more
like a historical sport.
Its expansive, 'heartfelt' melodic gestures sit badly with its
short-breathed 'symphonic' workings-out: one is disinclined to believe any
of them. Something analogous may eventually prove true of Leonard
Bernstein's 1977 Songfesttoo, a mixed bag of songs for six singers that
lurches wildly in different directions ' all of them familiar, from his own
earlier music and/or from his favourite models. While the huge impact of
Lenny-the-unbridled-musical-personality still reverberates, however, a
personal work such as Songfest is infernally interesting.
For a start, he chose his texts with the male lover for whom he briefly
abandoned his wife. Thus we get not only mordant reflections on marriage and
passion from Mistress Anne Bradstreet, Edna St Vincent Millay, Gertrude
Stein and the respectable Beats - Ferlinghetti, Corso  - but also Langston
Hughes - black, gay and narcissistic - and Walt Whitman in 'rough male kiss
of blankets' mood. Here that song went to the baritone Thomas Hampson,
eloquently straight, instead of the prescribed bass: presumably because
Brian Bannatyne-Scott was one of two last-minute stand-ins of the solo
sextet.
In the Stein duet, however, B-S. and Faye Robinson made cleverly wry
partners. Cynthia Clarey struck bright character in her every number; Jean
Rigby and young Salvatore Champagne, respectively the lowest and highest
voices among their sexes here, seized their opportunities to good effect.
How much Songfest amounts to is still unassessable, until Bernstein's own
psychodramas have become dry archive material. Now, we seem to hear Lenny
everywhere: in the West Side Story offshoots, in the sentimental Mahlerian
devices of his Whitman setting, even in the opening mock-chorale a la
Stravinsky.
Other Philharmonia/Slatkin concerts tonight and Monday, all sponsored by
Motorola.
</TEXT>
<XX>
