<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Books: Moistly unpleasant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHENA MACKAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE OF SPLENDIDISOLATION by Edna O'Brien Weidenfield &amp; Nicolson Pounds
14.99, 216 pages
Mention Edna O'Brien, and somebody is sure to exclaim: 'I loved the early
books]' Readers were enchanted by those green-eyed country girls and when
their heroines' lives became messy and urban, women looked back on their own
lost innocence. No writer, though, wants to be remembered only for the early
work, and since her starry debut O'Brien has produced a large oeuvre which
includes some superb short stories with sympathetic, sometimes beautiful and
scorned protagonists.
Unfortunately, it is difficult to feel anything kinder than exasperation
with Josie O'Meara, the heroine of House of Splendid Isolation, and O'Brien
has assembled such a cruel and prurient cast around her that it is hard to
know whom to dislike the most.
Josie, once beautiful, now old, ill and alone in her decaying mansion, might
excite more pity if she had not chosen to pay for the Big House in
humiliation and subservience to a brutish husband, or if she had not aborted
their child for unconvincing reasons. She would be easier to like if she had
not fantasised thus about the priest with whom she fell in love: 'To shower
him with things, wordly things, and the fruits of nature. Looking at the
thrushes so sleek and plump she longed to catch them with her bare hands and
grill them and serve them on toast for him, the way they did in Southern
Italy.' Her unconsummated affair with the priest made her a scandalous
woman.
She was inadvertently betrayed by Paud, who thought her 'the Queen of the
Munster Fairies'. Paud was also the unwitting cause of Josie's husband's
death when he persuaded him to hide a cache of weapons for the Fenians.
O'Meara, drunk as usual, was shot in a brawl with Guards. It was Josie who
tipped off the sergeant. Deranged with guilt, she wandered around sucking
the spittle from the stems of wild irises. 'Having to be put away for a
while. A small room in a nursing home named after St Jude Help of the
Hopeless.' Years later, Paud suggests to an IRA terrorist on the run that he
hide out in Josie's house.
McGreevy, known as the beast, breaks in and holds Josie hostage. A
delicately-handled relationship grows between them. That, and the scenes
involving the police pursuing McGreevy, show O'Brien at her best. Too often
elsewhere the prose goes stravaging and maundering down memory lane with its
hair streeling down and its clothes in flitters. Sometimes a remarkable
image is skewered on a sharp pin of observation, but those that linger are
moistly unpleasant.
There is a sickening complicity and voyeurism in the episode where Josie's
husband traps her in a sash window and beats her. Then there is lusty Brid,
the servant girl, who imagines herself with her lover: 'out of doors in the
soft unruly underlay of bog and bogland, everything seeping into her, his
instrument in tooraloora fettle.'
Josie's husband saw her as a horse: 'Her haunches were what he liked best,
wide and yet with a daintiness to them. A good mare.' When Josie is shot,
there is less sense of tragedy than of a wounded animal put out of its
misery after a wasted life. The crescendo and climax of the book are
excellent, but then Paud, who provided its portentous prologue, has to get
in on the act with a sententious epilogue. McGreevy was no more the
legendary hero Cuchulainn with whom he was compared than Josie was the Queen
of the Munster Fairies, although O'Brien succeeds in personifying two sides
of a seemingly insoluble problem; a much harder novel struggles to get out
of the bogland of history and whimsy, and sometimes breaks free.
</TEXT>
<XX>
