<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Books: Ancient nobility and modern prejudice - A
'monstrously unfair' study of the aristocracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL NICOLSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ASPECTS OF ARISTOCRACY: GRANDEUR AND DECLINE IN MODERN BRITAIN by David
Cannadine Yale University Press Pounds 19.95, 320 pages
The author of this uneven book has published another on the same theme, The
Pleasures of the Past, which he subtitled 'The Decline and Fall of the
British Aristocracy'.
In his new book the aristocracy is still on its way out, but not yet fallen.
The difference is significant. David Cannadine cannot deny that the
aristocracy has shown a remarkable capacity for survival, not so much in
power or esteem as in economic resilience.
A great part of the book is about money, its acquisition, investment and
profligate expenditure by titled families. It is a mopping-up of material
left over from the earlier book. He calls it a 'rather random accumulation'
of essays, and the effect is that of a thick mattress of compacted facts.
It is lively, deeply researched and thoroughly disagreeable. He finds little
to admire in what these families have achieved, except, strangely enough,
the Curzons' gift for staging stupendous shows like the Delhi Durbar.
He thinks the cult of the country house snobbish and nostalgic, as 'if the
owners of these houses were or are persons of greater merit than the rest of
us'. He is not a man to appreciate the audacity, beauty and irreplaceability
of these houses, nor of the works of art that they contain. In fact he is
not a man to find much joy in anything.
The delight that members of the aristocracy took, and still take, in
improving their estates, in their recreations, marriages and friendships are
to him all different forms of self-indulgence.
He faces a problem with the 19th century parvenus, whether to applaud their
breach of the aristocratic circle or to deplore their imitation of it. But
on the whole the class is depicted as contemptible and their survival, it is
strongly implied, is much to be regretted.
Cannadine illustrates his theme by examining the case-histories of a few
families and individuals. One of them is irrelevant, the Cozens-Hardy family
of Norfolk, brewers and solicitors, who gained a peerage, but in no other
sense claimed to be aristocrats. The others are Curzon, Lord Strickland of
Malta, Winston Churchill, the Dukes of Devonshire and my own parents, Harold
Nicolson and Vita Sackville-West.
The purpose of these pen-portraits is to show that on the whole the
aristocrats were a pretty poor lot. Cannadine may preface a chapter with the
caveat that so-and-so was remarkable, but then devotes the next 40 pages to
proving how unremarkable he was.
His chapter on Churchill is a good example. He is bound to acknowledge that
his performance in three years of his life, 1940-43, redeemed the rest of
it, but basically Churchill was selfish, snobbish, disreputable and, more
often than not, drunk.
His progenitors and children (all except Mary) were appalling examples of
aristocratic decadence. His extravagance threw him into the debt of
questionable men like Sir Ernest Cassel and Henry Strakosch. He cared little
for social reform, and his belief in democracy was largely humbug. He saw
himself as a British Mussolini.
Much of this portrait is undoubtedly true of Churchill, just as the Graham
Sutherland portrait of him was partly true. But both leave out the elements
of magnificence, daring, iconoclasm and the common touch which Cannadine
surprisingly concedes to Curzon. The other figures in this gallery escape
less lightly.
Lord Strickland was a failure, 'ridiculous in his self-importance'. The
Devonshires, whose finances are examined in detail, are credited with making
a killing with the development of Barrow-in-Furness, and then ridiculed for
losing it.
The eighth Duke emerges as one of the few men for whom Cannadine feels any
respect, because he restored the family's fortunes to the extent that the
present Duke is probably the richest of his line that there has ever been.
He cannot suppress a certain admiration for the aristocratic millionaire,
much as we might admire the Great Train Robbers.
I cannot be impartial in judging his long chapter about my parents. I think
it monstrously unfair that they should be taken as representative of all
that he finds most despicable in the combination of arrogance and flaccidity
in our aristocracy.
He has picked the wrong couple for this demonstration. He confuses elitism
with snobbishness. Vita and Harold came from the aristocracy, but were not
part of it. They despised and avoided The Tatler set. They inherited little,
but created much that was new, in literature politics, horticulture and
their concept of marriage.
The evidence, which is vast, is used selectively by Cannadine to sustain a
prejudice endemic to his whole approach.
</TEXT>
<XX>
