<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Travel: The last (or first) stop in western Europe -
Nicholas Woodsworth boards a train for Trieste, where the northern and the
Mediterranean world once fused
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS WOODSWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Who travels to Venice these days? Just about everybody, it seems. We were
gung ho, we were thousands strong, and we were in an Italian train heavily
armed with zoom lenses, phrase books, packsacks, guitar cases, travel bags
and video cameras.
We - British, American, German and a dozen other nationalities - were Gulf
allies. We were about to invade the Gulf of Venice. As I jumped off the
train at Mestre, the rail junction 10 minutes across the water from the
Venice station, I felt like a deserter: relieved.
Who, on the other hand, travels to Trieste these days? Just about no-one.
When the Trieste train pulled in at Mestre I found myself in a carriage with
just one other passenger. There were no video cameras on this train, but
gone, too, was that air of anticipation, that excited sociability that
envelops travellers on their way to much-celebrated, much-visited places.
Instead, there was a solitary man, in a plain white shirt, absorbed in a
technical manual on the transportation of liquid oxygen. I began to wonder
if my yearning for little-celebrated, little-visited places in Italy was
sensible after all.
I needed reassurance. I glanced at my map, following the rail line 100 miles
north and east of Venice. It snaked up and over the head of the Adriatic
Sea, then down a narrow corridor of Italian territory at the top of the
former Yugoslav coast. At the end of the corridor, squeezed against the
water and almost entirely surrounded by the new state of Slovenia, sat
Trieste.
I gazed at different coloured chunks on the map. The geography here was
improbable; it seemed to have little to do with the Italian world. Beyond
Slovenia, just 55 miles from Trieste and the Adriatic coast, lay Austria.
Not far to the north-east was Hungary. To the east, only 15 miles from
Trieste through Slovene territory, began Croatia; beyond it, Bosnia.
For western Europeans, Trieste sits at the end of the line. It lies in such
an unlikely corner of Italy that it had to be odd and interesting.
My problem was in recognising Trieste as Italian at all. Outside the railway
station there were road signs for Zagreb, Lubliana and the ferry to Albania.
Trabants and Zastavas mixed with Fiats and Fords. There were Italian voices
in the street, but Slovene and Croat, Hungarian and Czech ones as well.
More disorientating still, as I walked along the waterfront into the city
centre I found I had developed split vision. To my right lay the ships, the
docks, the languid early evening strollers of what was obviously a
Mediterranean port. But to my left, in domed and colonnaded pomp, sat a
perfectly preserved, 19th century neo-classical city - a miniature Prague,
Vienna or Budapest.
What had happened to the winding street, the grand confusion of
architecture, the anarchy of urban planning that makes up most Italian
cities? Here were broad, rectangular street patterns and large ceremonial
squares, bronze statues on plinths and vast stone buildings of uniform
height and window spacing. The whole thing was saved from heavy-handedness
only by pseudo-Greek marble statuary, fluted columns and fussily ornate
friezes on building facades.
I was confused. Here was imperial magnificence, weighty civic decorum -
order. It was most un-Italian. Mittel-Europa on the Adriatic? Only the
strangest of histories could account for it.
But I did not plumb the mysteries of Trieste's past that night. The city's
behaviour after dark is as un-Italian as its architecture. Where were the
crowds, the noise, the animation? Where were the young people? Wander where
I would, the only people I saw on the streets were grey and elderly. Trieste
was not only middle-European, it was a middle-European gerontocracy. By 9pm
the city had locked up and gone to bed. I went to bed, too.
I finally spotted some under-70s the next morning. They had just emerged
from a private English language school. We chatted. I asked them if they
knew of James Joyce. They did, of course - everyone in Trieste knows James
Joyce. He is a city celebrity. For more than a decade at the beginning of
the century Joyce, when he was not sitting writing in cafes, was teaching
English in Trieste classrooms. I wandered in.
I did not meet any avant-garde geniuses, but I did meet Richard Baudains, an
English writer who supports himself in the same time-honoured fashion. We
went out for a typical Trieste lunch, goulash.
The language business is booming these days in the city, Baudains told me,
but it is not a happy story. The local economy is shrinking, the city
population in decline, work scarce and young people acquiring every job
skill they can get before going to look for employment elsewhere.
Magnificent and neo-classical it may be, but Trieste - distant, isolated and
generally ignored - is little more than a wizened appendage of Italy.
It has not always been so. When Joyce lived there Trieste was at the centre
of things, a busy trading port, banking centre and continental crossroads
giving Mediterranean access to one of the greatest European states of all
time, the Austro-Hungarian empire.
If the city has an un-Italian feel, it is because it has only been Italian
for 75 years; until the end of the first world war and imperial collapse it
had been part of the Habsburg possessions for more than 600 years. After the
second world war it was only returned to Italy by the Allies in 1954. Even
today, Trieste's Italian-ness is disputed: after years of economic neglect
by Rome, a third of its citizens vote for some form of autonomy.
Why shouldn't the Triestini carry on being themselves, eating goulash, if
that is what they want, I ruminated over lunch. Not surprisingly, I found
they do a decent strudel, too. They also linger in cafes for hours and, like
the good folk of Vienna, read newspapers and contemplate political life.
Anyone who has watched Italians drink coffee or talk politics - they manage
to turn both into hurried and desperate acts - will appreciate the
difference, and realise that measured, ordered Trieste could never become
fully Italian. The more I walked around it, the more I saw Trieste as a
footnote to history, a city shorn of its function. It is like a stage set
after the cast of a drama has packed up and moved on.
Is it destined to be forgotten for-ever? Westerners may no longer pass
through the city on their way to holidays in Split, Dubrovnik and Greece.
Others have taken their place, though - the thousands of eastern Europeans
who swarm into the city avid not for luxury goods but basics like pots and
pans. What does Trieste look like to them, I wondered?
I hopped on a bus. Two hours later, in the Croatian port of Rijeka, I had
some idea of the answer. It looks pretty good. From Rijeka, Trieste is not
the end of the line but the start of one.
If Trieste is simply neglected, Rijeka is battered. Relief convoys roll
through town on their way south. On leave, weary soldiers in combat fatigues
sit in cafes. The civilians of Rijeka look poor and tired. Stubble here is
not a designer accessory for the trendy. Everyone has it. Even the women.
But the people of Trieste and Rijeka are not so different: they are victims
of a common, not-so-distant history. Before Croatian independence, before
Yugoslav control, before occupation by Italian fascists between the wars,
Rijeka was an imperial port. What Trieste was to the Austrians, Rijeka, her
sister city, was to the Hungarians - a meeting place with the Mediterranean
world.
Look behind the decay of the Rijeka waterfront and you will find remnants of
the same imperial magnificence found across the border, the same
heavy-handed authoritarian architecture, the same elegant, neo-classical
window-dressing.
In the bus on the way back to Trieste we began nervously rehearsing our
lines for the non-Croat-speaking officials waiting to trap us at the Italian
border.
'I am to shopping in Trieste,' we learned from the one English-speaking
Croat on the bus. 'I am to shopping in Trieste,' we all repeated under our
breaths for the next half-hour. I grew philosophical. The wheels of history
had turned before, and would turn again. Trieste was a place where the
northern and the Mediterranean world once fused. Perhaps it is where east
and west will fuse in the future. We are all parts of the historical
process.
Our missions explained, the border passed, we all got off the bus and went
shopping.
Trieste is only a two-hour train ride from Venice. Information can be
obtained from the Italian Tourist Board, No 1 Princes St, London W1R 8AY.
Tel: 071-408-1254. For the more adventurous, a trip to the Istrian peninsula
in Croatia is not as dangerous as it sounds: north-eastern Italians do it
all the time. Istria offers top-class Mediterranean sea-side facilities at
about half the Italian price.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
