<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Sport: Where have all the young men gone? - US Masters / Why
it would be good for golf if someone aged under 30 won at Augusta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEREK LAWRENSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Is it me or are golfers getting older these days? Here, for instance, were
the players favoured to win the US Masters: Greg Norman, Nick Price,
Bernhard Langer, Ben Crenshaw, Fuzzy Zoeller, and Nick Faldo.
Not one is under the age of 35. Jose-Maria Olazabal was described on
American television last week as having had a 'phenomenal career when you
consider all that he has achieved and he's still only 28.'
Heavens. Jack Nicklaus had won seven majors by the age of 28. Never mind
winning seven. Never mind winning one. Olazabal has only been in contention
to win on a couple of occasions.
Johnny Miller has some interesting things to say on the subject. You
remember Miller. He was the man who, 20 years ago, took scoring to another
level. Before Miller, a 66 or a 67 would get you the lead in a tournament.
If it was an easy course, someone would shoot 65. Miller shot 63. Not once
or twice, but on many occasions. Miller even shot 63 at Oakmont, which is
considered by many to be the toughest course on the US Open rota.
'I just don't understand what's going on,' he said. 'I've always believed,
and it was certainly true in my case, that 27-30 were the best years for a
golfer. That's when I shot the bulk of those scores.
'At 28, you stand over a 10ft putt and you know you're going to make it. At
35, you're still feeling pretty good and most of them go in. At 40, you just
breath a huge sigh of relief when it disappears below ground.' That was
then. Now, the only player in the top 12 in the world rankings who is under
the age of 30 is Davis Love, and even he reaches that landmark age next
week. The only players under the age of 25 in the top 50 are Ernie Els from
South Africa and the American, Phil Mickelson. There is not one British
player in that age group in the top 100.
'I think the Europeans must be wondering if anyone is ever going to come
along to replace the Faldos and the Langers and the Seves,' said Miller.
'They are all around the age of 36 and without being disrespectful to the
young guys, you just can't see a player on the horizon who is going to make
the impact on the game that they have made in the last decade.' Tony Jacklin
was 25 when he won the Open, and a year older when he won the US Open. He
was burnt out at 35. So was Miller, and so was Watson.
Raymond Floyd, 23 when he won the US PGA Championship, remains a contender
almost 30 years on. Floyd said: 'I can't give you a direct answer as to why
the players who are in their 20s are no longer winning majors, but l can
tell you why the top professionals are having longer careers these days.
'The overriding factor is the way technology has improved both the golf club
and the golf ball. I'm obviously nowhere near as strong or as agile as I was
when I was 25, but I hit the ball, if anything, further than I did then
because the equipment is now so much better.'
There are other explanations. Diet, for one thing. The pros have joined the
health beat. They eat bananas instead of burgers. They drink Gatorade rather
than Glenfiddich. Said Miller: 'There was certainly a lot more nightlife
when I was on tour. The players are much more family-orientated now, and the
growth of the prize funds has helped in that respect. The players are
earning so much that they can afford to have their wives and children travel
to every tournament.'
Money is also a consideration in another respect. The remarkable growth of
the senior's tour in America has meant that the players have every incentive
to prolong their careers beyond middle age.
All of which explains why many players are now finding that some of their
best years occur when they reach their late 30s. But why are all of the top
nine players in the world aged between 34 and 39?
Why are there currently only two players under the age of 30 who have won
major championships? Why are there only four, indeed, whose ages fall
outside that seemingly magical 34-39 bracket?
Miller says: 'Maybe we're just going through one of those dormant periods
when there are no good young players around or certainly not ones you can
compare to previous generations. But it will turn around again. You will get
one player in his late twenties 20s who will win a couple of majors and then
he will inspire his peers.
'That's what happened with the Europeans. First, Ballesteros won the
Masters, and Langer said to himself: 'Well, if he can do it, so can I' And
then when he won, Faldo started to believe that he could claim a green
jacket. And so on. It will happen again.'
It would be good for golf if it happened at Augusta this weekend.
</TEXT>
<XX>
