<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Food and Drink: Pauillac rivals join hands at an English
chateau - Lafite and Mouton-Rothschild have combined to show their full
range
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDMUND PENNING-ROWSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The two adjoining, sometime rival, first-growth Pauillacs - Lafite and
Mouton-Rothschild - have combined to bring examples of all their companies'
wines to the UK. Not through the usual trade channels, but in a shop in the
refurbished Waddesdon Manor near Aylesbury (described in the Weekend FT of
March 26). This is the only place in the world where all can be bought: from
Lafite's Chilean Los Vascos '92 (Pounds 6.20) to its grand vin '82 (Pounds
135), and Mouton's Mouton-Cadet '90 (Pounds 6.50) to the California Opus One
'88 (Pounds 42.70).
Waddesdon, the late 19th century 'French Chateau in England' built for Baron
Ferdinand de Rothscild, was left by his great-nephew James in 1957 to the
National Trust. But the main responsibility for its running has remained
with the Rothschild family. Lord (Jacob) Rothschild has now filled the
original cellars with his personal reserve: 11,000 bottles from Lafite,
supplemented with 3,000 from Mouton. This starts with a magnum of Lafite
1870, followed by 35 vintages, fine, indifferent and poor, up to 1970. The
Moutons begin with a present from Baroness Philipine of half a dozen bottles
from 1867 (the vintage before Lafite passed into Rothschild hands) to 1896.
For the visitor this is museum stuff, an appendage to the tour of the house,
and the wines are binned behind three locked gates though the rest of the
handsome cellars, decorated with photographs of the chateau and the Mouton
labels, are open to inspection.
However, in a newly-created shop on the garden level, wines from more than
30 appellations or brands are for sale. In the last 30 years both estates
have greatly widened their interests. In Bordeaux, Lafite has added
Duchart-Milon, Rieussel and L'Evangile, and then spread to Los Vascos in
Chile and the distinguished Quinta do Carmo in Portugal.
Mouton acquired adjoining Clerc-Milon and then joined Mondavi in California
for Opus One, but most of its expansion has been to increase its Bordeaux
brands, including Medoc, St Emilion and Graves Baron Philippe. All dozen are
on sale at Waddesdon, where Lafite also has a Waddesdon Manor Pauillac '90
(Pounds 10.15)
Clearly no attempt has been considered to by-pass their traditional trade
channels, so Waddesdon is not a place to go for bargains. The sommelier,
Henry Beaumont, describes prices as 'fair', and nowhere else in the UK could
such a selection be found, including all the grands vins of Lafite and
Mouton from 1981 (around Pounds 75) to 1990 (Pounds 80 to Pounds 85)
respectively for these vintages: dearer than at auction per dozen, but not
there for single bottles.
Testings by outside bodies will be encouraged, and the Wine Society of
Stevenage, Herts, will hold the first for its members on May 12. Also the
shop is organising them on two levels. On the second Saturday morning of
each month (the next on May 14) a varied, tutored tasting will be set up at
Pounds 20 a head, and then on Wednesdays June 1, July 29, September 7 and 28
and October 12 de luxe tutored tastings will be held, including lunch and a
tour of the house, at Pounds 45 a head.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2084 Wines, Brandy and Brandy Spirits.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
