<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Gardening: So how does a beginner learn to begin? - Tamara
Hedge-Bonus starts by ignoring the advice of the new radio experts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBIN LANE-FOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The narcissi have never looked better; we can be busy this weekend with
everything which the gales stopped us doing over Easter. Spare a thought,
however, for the new recruits to the real business of life, those for whom
1994 may be the start of a lifetime of gardening until arthritis stops them
in the 2030s. In fact, 2030 is way beyond the time scale of the new
horticultural intake who have been kind enough to share their progress with
me. They sold it short six months ago - one reason why gardening is now
within their reach.
With the passing of April 5, a green glimmer on the horizon has fallen on
the plate glass headquarters of the City stronghold of Goldmine Fax. Like
players on the old Monopoly board, the teams on the 13th and 14th floors
have just passed 'Go' and collected the fruits of their year's derivative
efforts.
Only one colleague has collected more than Tamara Hedge-Bonus. Aged 32, she
has hedged and re-hedged round the clock. She battered the franc in August;
she put Italian bonds back to back with Norman Lamont's least wanted bits of
farewell paper. By the terms of her clients' Special Reserve, she is now
entitled to a personal incentive payment of Pounds 600,000 to meet the
rigours of the new tax year. A man on the 14th floor is entitled to Pounds
820,000 and, in February, it did look as if Tamara was going to beat him.
But the US Treasury caught her off-balance on the very Friday evening when
she had left early to spend quality time with Chris.
Chris and she are not married because Tamara always fights shy of open-ended
contracts. On the company paperwork, he is ranked as her spouse alternative
and there are times, to be honest, when Tamara wonders if other alternatives
might be better value. Cool, pure nerve is the hallmark of the Hedge-Bonus
style in action, inferring fair value from conventional things like maths.
Chris, by contrast, works for World Wildlife and moves at an altogether more
suggestible pace. To her annoyance (and sub-conscious pleasure), she can
boss him mercilessly; her friends know, as she half-knows, that he
represents her conscience.
One more year, Tamara tells herself, and then she will be out of it. Banking
a second bonus will see her through life, with some gentle dealing from
home. Being out of it means being partly in the country, where Tamara and
her generation have talked often of applying their new finances to attaining
the standards of a past age.
Tamara has secured her property already: a dower house with a wing for
future small Hedge-Bonuses and stabling which could accommodate a 'phone,
fax and serious PC. The ground slopes bumpily to a superlative view from a
Cotswolds escarpment, and down further to a chain of neglected lakes
(Chris's present paradise but one, she tells herself privately, which will
still stack up even if he does not).
Tamara is a gardener with a vision. In her past, she looks back to idyllic
years by Surrey's Bluebell Railway before her parents quarrelled, split up,
and she developed that ruthless calculation which has paid off so handsomely
in her present career. In those early days, there were buttercups; the woods
were alive with white anemones; and roses tumbled in clouds from old stone
walls. Tamara learnt so much from her mother before her mother became
embittered: she grew up knowing that red salvia was only for vulgar Italians
and that high-class gardens had atmosphere and form.
How, though, does a beginner know how to begin? High-flying friends on the
14th floor have been telling Tamara for years that she will end up restoring
furniture and listening to Gardeners' Question Time. When the BBC's entire
team decamped to the opposition, Tamara found herself sympathising with a
tactic much discussed in her department. She found herself feeling even more
sympathetic when the new team was presented as the BBC's bid for a younger
audience. Feeling biddable, Tamara set the recorder on last week's midday
episode and used the Easter markets' closure to discover what beginners
should do when they begin.
Hedge-Bonuses are not unadaptable, and she quite understood that the BBC had
chosen to broadcast its programme from a building site in Manchester owned
by a northern housing association. Gardening, her father had always told
her, is gardening wherever you do it, and the same advice applies whoever
you are.
It did cross her mind that this particular community centre was rather too
close for comfort to the Enterprise Zone where the 1990 bonus had been
invested rashly in an over-valued white elephant of an office project.
Nonetheless, she and the Manchester young would have to start somewhere.
She had not expected them to start with quite so many condescending
references to their listeners' enthusiasm, or so many nervous giggles to
show that the questions were appealing to the young. The new panel almost
persuaded her that all you have to do when a sub-contractor leaves you with
rubble in the garden is to ask him to bring in top-soil and break up
whatever is underneath.
She then remembered her formative years as a construction sector analyst and
wondered if Ann on the BBC panel understood why every builder prefers to
take a short cut. She wondered even more when the panel told a young
enthusiast to plant Jerusalem artichokes as a boundary round their allotment
and use quinces as a screen to filter out cats.
Hedge-Bonuses know about hedges: why land these beginners with artichokes
which run everywhere and look absolutely miserable in winter on her uncle's
farm? Why suggest quinces which would not even keep out her mother in
shorts, let alone a cat on the run from the nearby motorway?
The panel had much to say about assembling old drink cartons and cutting out
their bottoms to make cheap seed boxes: Tamara remembered the young man at
Goldmines who grew lillies in the office champagne crates back in the bubbly
summer of 1987. When the panel moved on to trees, she wondered whether it
ever had managed them? How could it recommend birches for 'youngsters to
climb in?' When the young saplings would snap at the touch?
When Ann proposed elder bushes so that the community could make elder
champagne, Tamara wondered if she had ever seen the scores of unwanted
elders which had seeded themselves so annoyingly on the embankment and in
the back gardens along Tamara's morning journey to work on the London Tube.
The more they talked, the more she saw through it. Why did these
enthusiastic northern house-persons have to be told to grow a patch of
brambles, break up their drink cartons, plant elder bushes and berberis and
experiment with a turf roof? Tamara remembered Chris's photographs from
Greenland on his last expedition to Save the Seal. He had photographed the
turf igloos of Eskimo Greenland, maintained as mementos of a past. Were they
really wanted in the Manchester area?
Why did nobody mention roses and lilacs, daffodils, orange blossom and
everything else which gardeners want to know how to grow elsewhere? Why
would the younger generation be attracted by ideas which ignored beauty,
quality and form: an aromatherapy garden, pitcher plants to catch the
occasional wasp, and herb beds with quotations from outdated Herbals,
inscribed on plaques?
When it came to wild life, Tamara lost her remaining faith. The entire panel
seemed to want to patronise the under-40s and make them attract wildlife,
whereas sensible gardeners want to keep it out. The members even expanded on
the belief that 'native trees attract native wild life.' Had they never seen
butterflies on Chinese buddleias, or bullfinches playing merry hell on
Japanese cherries? What are these 'natives,' anyway: is the BBC so
horticulturally incorrect?
At every turn, the willing Hedge-Bonus sensed condescension and mock
'enthusiasm' which was being fobbed off with gimmicky ideas that nobody had
tried in life. The one thing she knows is what her father told her:
beginners are beginners, on Manchester rubbish or among Cotswold ivy, and
neither wants elder bushes or rabbits burrowing into a turf roof.
This weekend, Tamara and her consort will not be listening to programmes
which try to patronise questioners. It will take time, but she has decided
to go for a track record, stick with it, and ignore the new siren voices
mounted on a bandwagon for the sake of the change of image. Admittedly,
Chris rather liked the idea of turfing the roof of the dower house
outbuildings - until she pointed out that he would have to mow it, and that
the last thing they wanted was worms above gutter level.
In search of a mentor, she has turned instead to the senior head of her
department and received the right advice for any new beginner: go out and
buy proven titles by the late Arthur Hellyer, former FT gardening writer,
and count yourself lucky that you can rely on a lifetime which made the
mistakes before you. This week, Chris has found The Amateur Gardener in a
Cheltenham bookshop and he and Tamara will be starting from the beginning
with their radios firmly switched off.
</TEXT>
