<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Around the horns in 15 minutes: David Lascelles (and 63
others) give Wagner a dashing work-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was a box with a chain saw at one side of the rehearsal room, which
was rather disconcerting. But perhaps the prospect of listening to an
orchestra consisting entirely of French horns playing a Wagner medley might
not be to everyone's taste.
It did not, however, daunt the 64 members of the British Horn Society who
turned up at the Barbican Centre in the City of London on Easter Saturday to
prepare for a rare performance of Fantasia on Themes from the Ring of the
Nibelungen, by Vitali Bujanovski.
As a thoroughly indifferent horn player, I was one of the more apprehensive,
but I had been assured that my modest grade six attainment was sufficient. I
also had the attendant support of my wife, another relative novice.
Bujanovski, who died only last year, was for many years principal horn of
the Leningrad Symphony Orchestra and, like many lovers of the French horn,
he was unable to resist the call of The Ring. Wagner himself is reputed to
have told his wife that he 'wished he could write for nothing but horns.'
Bujanovski took up the challenge and reduced the entire Ring cycle to its
bare essentials: brass. He scored his piece for 32 individual horn parts in
eight separate groups. But the orchestration is so clever that it can be
played by any number of horns in multiples of eight.
This extraordinary work lasts only 15 minutes but it packs in all the
juiciest thematic highlights: the Rhine, Siegfried's heroics, the majesty of
Valhalla, Wotan's fury, etc. It is the sort of thing everyone should hear -
just once.
When we arrived at the Barbican, we were invited to leaf through sample
parts to find the one that suited us best. My wife and I ended up with part
30 which was low, had lots of rests and only one exposed bit, where we
introduced the 'Siegfried Assertive' motif. Since no one has yet actually
got round to publishing the Fantasia, we all had to make do with
hand-written, photo-copied parts.
Our co-players were a varied bunch of all shapes, sizes and ages, most of
them amateur enthusiasts. Many were silver-haired; others were well below
the age of puberty but possessing talent which left you wondering: Why
bother?
More interesting, in a way, were the horns themselves. Few instruments are
quite as exhibitionistic, with their shiny twirls and complicated valve
mechanics. Three owners of Vienna horns had come down specially from
Scotland: their horns had an extra loop near the mouthpiece which invited
eager comment and comparison.
Purveyors of horns, music for the horn, and all the bits and pieces that
horn players need had laid on a little exhibition in the hallway. With much
fingering, tootling and chattering, we made our way round the stands. One of
the problems with the horn is the shortage of good music, and this was a
chance to extend our repertoire (although we have yet to find out whether
our purchase of a Schubert mass arranged for horn duet was a good buy).
The day's schedule involved only a brief rehearsal directly before the
actual performance. We were lucky to have as our conductor Sian Edwards, the
music director of the English National Opera; lucky, because she is a horn
player herself.
All musicians think their instrument is the most difficult of all to play,
but French horn players know it happens to be true in their case. The
instrument is a rebellious creature: it disobeys even the sternest commands.
But Edwards, her shock of red hair ablaze, knew how to coax the best from
our unruly efforts. The ragged early sounds, the disconcerting wrong notes,
the false entries - all were ironed out steadily as we grew familiar with
the piece, and each other.
An hour later, we trooped on to the stage of the Barbican concert hall, a
venue where I had never in my wildest dreams imagined I would find myself.
The lights shone down with blinding brightness and I could barely see the
audience, although one reason might have been that it was not exactly large.
Edwards raised her hands, caught our eyes and off we went. First, she drew
out the sonorous opening bars of the Rhinegold, then increased the pace as
we joined Siegfried in his adventures. The tension rose as we clashed with
the mounting forces of evil: great eruptions of noise as we slew the dragon
and charged on to defy the very gods themselves.
Next, a change of pace as we thrilled to the joys of eternal youth, rode
down the mighty Rhine, and galloped to the sound of Siegfried's horn.
The climax came with two dozen horns trilling and the rest providing a huge
body of supporting sound, with an urgent, punctuating beat from deep below.
Then, with a final thunderous blast, it was all over.
That, at least, was how it seemed from the back row. Whether the audience
felt the same, I do not know. There was plenty of applause, and Edwards came
back for a second bow, waving generously at our happy faces.
And so we dispersed. I only hope we left Wagner beaming, not spinning in his
grave.
</TEXT>
<XX>
