<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Minding Your Own Business: Must try harder to do the tax
return - Computing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEAN MILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bright new versions of all the principal home budget computer programs have
blossomed with spring: Intuit's Quicken, Microsoft Money, and Sage
Moneywise.
All are Windows programs, and all represent significant improvements on
earlier versions. Two years ago I would have fainted for joy at the features
offered by any. Now I am exasperated that no-one has got it quite right.
I must begin by declaring an interest: I worked with Intuit through the
winter helping to anglicise parts of the Quicken manual. I expressed my
exasperation to them directly.
I have several years of computer account-keeping behind me now.
I like knowing exactly how much we have in our various accounts. Tax returns
are easier. Reconciling a bank statement is almost fun by computer, and does
reveal mistakes - usually mine, sometimes the bank's. I do not bother much
these days with reports and graphs. I do not even do much budgeting any
more, now that I can turn back so easily to last year's figures.
All three programs meet these needs admirably. All three, but especially
Quicken and Moneywise, have new features, both useful and fun. And all can
calculate and report on VAT, making them suitable for small businesses.
Sage Moneywise is much easier to use than it used to be, but it remains
unashamedly a computerised cashbook. The two American programs, Quicken and
Money, include provision for accrual accounting. I think Quicken is the
better of the two.
Included in the box with Moneywise is a separate program to calculate the
interest you should be paying or receiving on bank accounts.
Amid all this excellence, what do I find to complain about? Just this: these
programs do not provide the help I want with my tax return.
Both Quicken and Money claim to offer help with tax. In Quicken, income and
expense categories can be assigned to particular questions on the standard
tax forms and drawn together in a tax report. Wonderful? No. Because neither
program has included provision for the tax deducted from bank and building
society accounts, or for tax credits received with dividends. You can devise
categories for these items and include them in your accounts - but it will
not do you much good, because you cannot get the information out again in a
useful form.
Quicken was the first domestic accounts program in this country to
incorporate a stockmarket module. Now all three have them. Although even the
best (Quicken) is not a substitute for dedicated portfolio management
software - I like and use this feature.
An investment performance report, offered by Microsoft Money as well,
assesses performance from any date to any other date, taking everything into
account - dividends, profits and losses, dealing costs, and changes in
capital value. The result is expressed as a percentage of the value of the
portfolio at the beginning of the chosen time span. This is one report I use
regularly. Quicken gives the return on our portfolio in 1993 as 16.5 per
cent, not counting tax credits - that sounds all right.
Microsoft Money has been imperfectly anglicised, with the result, among
other oddities, that shares cannot be arranged according to stock market
sector. Sage's portfolio is not fully integrated with the rest of the
program.
My husband and I own most of our share portfolio jointly, but for historical
reasons, we each have some shares in our sole names. Most of the time we
think of the whole lot as 'the shares', without distinction. I need a
program which allows me to divide the shares into different accounts
according to ownership, but view and update them together. In Quicken and
Microsoft Money, but not Sage Moneywise, this is easily done. It is a
valuable feature. It means, for example, that each of your personal equity
plans could be placed in an account of its own, but merged with each other
and the rest of your portfolio when required. So far so good.
At income tax time, proper distinctions must be made. My summers are
darkened by the need to draw up lists for our tax returns of his dividends,
her dividends, their dividends; his shares-in-lieu, her shares-in-lieu,
their shares-in-lieu; and then the gilts and the unit trusts and finally, in
a little list all of their own, my husband's four dividends from Bowater,
including income from savings and investments abroad.
Quicken offers many report formats, all capable of a variety of
modifications, but will not produce a simple list of dividends and tax
credits. Microsoft Money has not even heard of tax credits. Sage Moneywise,
being British, will produce the list. But Sage makes no provision for
shares-in-lieu, and will not let me merge the portfolios.
Does no one besides myself mind? I feel that these otherwise excellent
programs have invited my discontent by promising 'tax reports'. If I use
either Quicken or Money for a year, all the information the tax man wants
will be there, carefully typed in and verified as bank accounts are
reconciled. I want to click my mouse and see the lists roll out of my
printer. Maybe next spring?
These programs require an IBM-compatible computer running MS-DOS version 3.1
or higher and Microsoft Windows.
Money Version 3 costs about Pounds 50, including VAT. Telephone:
0734-270001.
Moneywise Version 2 costs Pounds 49 plus VAT. It requires Windows 3.1 and at
least 2 MB of memory (RAM); 4 MB is recommended. Telephone: 091-2013000.
Quicken 3 for Windows costs Pounds 59.95 including VAT. It requires Windows
3.1 and at least 2 MB of RAM. Telephone: 0800-585058.
</TEXT>
