FT  09 APR 94 / How to Spend it: The very easy chair - A look at cardboard
furniture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fun for children, for students, for week-end houses or anywhere where
cheapness matters, is the cardboard chair designed by the French architect,
Oliver Leblois. The chairs are sold in flat-packs and are a doddle to
assemble. They are made from triple-layer corrugated cardboard and are said
to be strong enough to withstand weights of up to 21 stone. In other words,
in spite of being made from what is, after all, only paper, they really are
meant for sitting on.
These, you will have gathered, are not chairs for posh drawing-rooms - they
are chairs to have fun with, to be used in nurseries, kitchens, playrooms,
bedsitters. They come in plain cardboard and the enterprising can paint or
decorate them as they will. There are also two sizes - the adults' version
which sells at Pounds 26, the child's one which sells for Pounds 15 and
includes a pack of crayons (with which to decorate the chair) in the kit.
After Noah, of 121, Upper Street, Islington, London N1, (telephone:
071-359-4281) sells them and will soon have more cardboard furniture from
the range - bookshelves, table and even a bed are to follow. As the chairs
are flat-packed they can be ordered by mail for an extra Pounds 5 to cover
postage and packing.
