<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: Pibs that bear watching - Bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DYSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gilts and sterling bonds have been among the worse performers in the first
quarter of this year. But the capital value matters only when you sell your
investment and, with most bonds, you have the comfort of a fixed repayment
date, and value, for which to hold on.
Permanent interest-bearing shares (Pibs) offer only one, albeit enhanced,
virtue - a fixed income, since there is no repayment date.
Now, First National and the Cheshire Building Society have issued floating
rate Pibs. Since the interest rate is changed every six months and the
issuer never repays the capital, such an investment would appear not to
offer any of the benefits enjoyed by holders of other bonds.
But with concern growing over the direction of interest rates, a bond from
which the income will rise in line with these is attractive, especially if
the capital does not fluctuate greatly. We must, however, put this in
context.
The Cheshire (ranked 22nd-largest society) issue will, every six months,
re-fix the income it pays by adding 2.4 percentage points to the six-monthly
rate paid by Libor - the London Interbank Offered Rate, which is the rate of
interest in the short-term wholesale market. What is more, the Cheshire
promises to do this forever. At present, the six-monthly Libor rate plus 2.4
percentage points equates to an interest rate of a little under 8 per cent.
But it is easy to forget that Pibs are the lowest quality share issued by
the societies and rank among the last creditors in liquidation. With
conventional Pibs, the high fixed yield offers some compensation for this
risk. But the return from floating Pibs should be compared with deposits.
Some deposit accounts from larger societies offer full repayment of capital
and no dealing charges as well as rates close to those of floating Pibs.
Thus, investors must question the merits of these Pibs.
Michael Dyson is a director of BZW Capital Markets. This is a market-maker
and cannot deal direct with private clients. Readers wanting to buy bonds
should see a broker.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
