<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: Directors' transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIVIEN MACDONALD, The Inside Track
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Inchcape's results at the beginning of the week reflected a strong Japanese
yen and were lower than expected. The share price fell back a little and
both Charles MacKay, the chief executive, and Sir David Plastow, the
chairman, bought stock.
Flying Flowers is based in the Channel Islands and deals in fresh blooms.
The company was floated in August of last year and the share price has
blossomed considerably since then. Most of the board held stock when the
company came to market but the purchase by D. Payne of 50,000 shares
represents his entire holding.
Calderburn, which makes office furniture, warned about profits in December
following the impact of deferred orders. At the same time, it announced it
had acquired SBFI, which makes specialist desks. This has proved a
successful deal and the company started the year strongly. We note that the
sale of stock by Fredrich-Wilhelm Dauphin was made on behalf of his wife; he
retains almost 3.5m shares.
Devro International makes sausage skins and came to the market in July 1993.
At that point, the directors undertook not to sell any stock until after the
results were announced last month. When these were announced, three board
members then sold shares. All retain considerable stakes in the company,
though.
