<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Finance and the Family: A GP among the specialists - 11th in
a series on fee-based advisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOANNA SLAUGHTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Andrew Swallow is clear about his role as a fee-based independent financial
adviser. He says he acts as his clients' general practitioner, not their
specialist.
If they need a financial service that Swallow believes can be undertaken
better, or more cost-effectively, by someone else, he calls on his
established professional connections among accountants, solicitors and
stockbrokers. Similarly, he and his colleague, Sarah Keens, do not undertake
discretionary investment management.
He says: 'I don't think a small IFA can run a discretionary service because
this requires full-time skills. We can't see how a small organisation can
maintain the skills necessary to provide structural investment and financial
advice and, at the same time, undertake the specialist work necessary to
manage funds on a discretionary basis.'
Swallow is the founder of Andrew Swallow IFA, based in Ipswich, Suffolk, and
established four years ago. A previous winner of Money Management's
independent financial adviser competition, he used to work in the insurance
industry and also spent four years in an IFA partnership.
This broke up because Swallow wanted to work exclusively on a fee basis. He
argues: 'When IFAs charge commission, the only difference between them and
the direct salesman is that they can sell lots of policies while the Allied
Dunbar salesman can sell only one.'
Although Swallow works from a large, modern bungalow close to the
countryside, his clients tend to be concentrated in the Greater London area.
'We get them from recommendations and professional connections,' he says. 'I
was lucky that I was with a Lloyd's brokerage in London for two years.'
Swallow describes his 'average financial planning client' as earning more
than Pounds 75,000 a year and/or having total assets of more than Pounds
500,000. This dominance by the better-off is one that he regrets but feels
is inevitable.
'It is a great distress to me that the people who would benefit most from
independent financial advice cannot afford to pay for it,' he says. 'We will
consider any size of funds on our personal financial planning side, but our
fees make it unlikely that we will undertake investments of less than Pounds
100,000. We all do occasional charity cases - re-arranging modest affairs
without charge - but you can't run a business on these. My view is that IFAs
eventually will deal only with the wealthiest 5 per cent.'
Swallow's fees are time-based and range from Pounds 45 to Pounds 110 an
hour. Clients are always consulted on the treatment of any commissions that
arise. 'We are fully computerised and we itemise the bill for every item,'
he says. 'We are just moving to a new system that times by the second. I
feel that a financial adviser who is treating clients' investments has to be
even more transparent on fees and commissions than an accountant or
solicitor.'
Swallow also points out that: 'Far too much of the work is non-productive
nowadays. That's why fees have to be so ridiculously high. You have to do so
much research, reading and training.'
The Swallow service starts with an assessment of all a client's assets. This
includes a detailed investment policy schedule and an individual balance
sheet and cash flow forecast. The analysis can take three to six months to
complete.
'Once we know the extent of a new client's assets and have agreed these with
them, we can provide the appropriate advice,' explains Swallow.
'Typically, our clients tend to be very busy in their own life, earning a
lot of money, and they want that portion of their affairs sorted out for
them.
'You often find that the most brilliant and successful people are absolutely
clueless in my department. Then again, some are very difficult to deal with
because they are so big and you have to be quite forceful sometimes to bring
them to the table. I sometimes say to people: 'If you would do this, or if
you would reply to correspondence, I could cut my fees in half'.'
Swallow also draws up financial plans for small businesses, and manages
employee benefit arrangements. Roughly one-third of the firm's income comes
from its 29 corporate clients.
'We act predominantly for small PLCs, director-owned companies and
partnerships,' says Swallow. 'We produce our own member booklets. I find it
extraordinary that most IFAs who do corporate benefits wouldn't dream of
doing their own booklets, as they are in the best position for this.'
He places great importance on client contact, arguing that one of the
strengths of a fee-based firm over one based on commission is the ability to
forge close relationships. Private clients receive quarterly bulletins and
an annual review, and Swallow says: 'It is unusual for us to speak to a
client fewer than two or three times each year. A lot of clients contact us
once a month.' He also has monthly contacts with corporate clients.
Swallow adds: 'We try to be pro-active. But, as we are paid by the hour, we
have to be somewhat circumspect to ensure that clients do not feel we are
trying to drum up fees on their account.'
THE INDEPENDENTS
