<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Markets: Jitters shake the builders - The Bottom Line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares of construction and building material companies, like the rest of the
stock market, are suffering an attack of the jitters. Fears about possible
interest rate rises, which have depressed stock markets worldwide, have been
accompanied by concern that previous optimism over the pace and quality of
the housebuilding and construction recovery could have been overdone.
As a result, construction shares have fallen sharply, in spite of a return
to profits by businesses which, only a year ago, were announcing record
losses.
Amec, the large UK construction, engineering and property group, was the
latest to be affected with shares falling 5p to 135p on Thursday despite
unveiling a Pounds 21m pre-tax profit last year following a Pounds 88.2m
loss in 1992.
The turnaround was lower than expected, but what really concerned the market
were remarks, made by chairman Sir Alan Cockshaw, about the continuing poor
state of UK construction - in particular, the low profit margins (some would
say, non-existent) on many domestic jobs.
The problem, as Cockshaw made clear, was that there were too many companies
chasing too little work. The industry was in sore need of rationalisation
but he did not believe this was likely to happen.
Over-capacity was such that margins were likely to remain dull even when
output recovered. In consequence, this year was likely again to be tough;
shareholders would have to wait until 1995 for recovery.
By then, however, the UK industry will be facing public spending cuts on
roads and other infrastructure. These may be offset, only partially, by
increased private investment.
The answer, according to Amec, is to pursue higher margin work overseas or
try to establish long-term relationships with customers to reduce dependence
on conventional competitive bidding where margins are likely to remain thin.
Similar comments have been made by other UK contractors during this results
season, suggesting that competition even for these kinds of projects is
likely to be intense.
Neither is the outlook for housebuilders as unclouded as might once have
appeared. This is one sector of the industry where output is rising sharply.
Margins also have begun to recover as expensive land, bought late in the
1980s, has been used up.
The problem, according to Howard Seymour, construction analyst with
stockbroker Barclays de Zoete Wedd, is that the rise in housebuilders' share
prices over the past 12 months suggests that investors expect profits to
rise faster than might be achieved.
'It is difficult,' says Seymour, 'to see where the earnings are going to
come from to justify the multiples some of these shares stand at - unless we
return to climate of high house price inflation.'
Particular concern has been caused by the way in which land prices have been
chased up as builders seek to replenish depleted stocks. According to David
Wilson, chairman of Wilson Bowden - which announced an 85 per cent rise in
pre-tax profits to Pounds 31.2m last year - prices for quality sites have
risen by an average of 20 per cent nationally, and by up to 50 per cent in
south-east England, during the past 12 months. But Wilson says house prices,
in a low inflation environment, are unlikely to rise enough to justify such
a big increase in land costs.
Building material companies have been more successful in reducing capacity
and costs and, therefore, are more likely to gain from increases in volume.,
They are even managing to increase prices - particularly in industries where
there are only a few players, such as plasterboard and cement.
This situation does not apply to all materials. Hepworth created another
flurry of concern on the stock market when it announced that over-capacity
was still affecting many of its products, inhibiting price recovery.
Mark Stockdale construction analyst with SG Warburg, says: 'Given that stock
market valuations have assumed that earnings recovery would accelerate, any
perceived inability to deliver will be punished.'
</TEXT>
