<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Blood brothers: a Zulu tragedy: Patti Waldmeir travels to
rural Natal to meet a family divided by South Africa's deadly political
geography
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a hill in South Africa's Natal province - a place of many, many
hills - which is known as Patheni, or 'the place of goodness.' The poignant
beauty of the name is a cruel joke played on those who live in the two rival
villages separated by its blue-green ridge, including brothers Samuel and
Joseph Njilo, childhood playmates turned mortal enemies by the deadly
geography of Natal.
For it is not so much politics which separates Samuel from Joseph in this
remote area of the Natal midlands: few in either village know much about the
rival parties which have turned Natal into a battleground for the Inkatha
Freedom Party and the African National Congress. It is the hill which
divides them.
Geography determines many political choices in Natal. Those who live in
Inkatha areas will not vote, because Inkatha says they must not; and those
who live in ANC areas will vote because they do not dare to stay away.
Patheni and Ndaleni, the two rival villages which sprawl across the valleys
on either side of Patheni hill, are two such areas. Joseph, younger
'brother' to Samuel (Europeans would say they are cousins) does not seem to
find this strange. How is it, I ask, that they have ended up, 40 years after
their shared childhood, on opposite sides of the political divide? Why did
one brother join the ANC and the other the IFP? 'Because one stays (lives)
at Patheni and the other at Ndaleni,' says Joseph. For him, it is as simple
as that.
In 1990, he says, his own village of Ndaleni held a meeting and decided
unanimously to join the ANC. The decision had to be unanimous, he says;
Ndaleni could not accommodate opposing viewpoints. 'If I didn't join the
ANC, I would have had to move to Patheni,' he says, without the slightest
hint of resentment. 'Nobody would dare stay here who is not ANC,' adds his
wife Catherine, while daughters Promise and Gloria contribute their
explanation of how Ndaleni became an ANC village: 'At the beginning, people
were forced to join the ANC. Now they love it.'
Samuel does not pretend that things are much different in Patheni, a few
arduous kilometres away by foot across the top of Patheni hill: 'Even here,
people say they are IFP when really they are ANC because they've got houses
here and they know it's too expensive to build another house'. Faced with
that overwhelming economic imperative it will be a brave man who votes with
his conscience and not with his neighbours (especially since Inkatha's poll
boycott will mean that mere presence at the voting station will almost
certainly mean a vote for the ANC).
Fighting has left several hundred dead in the two communities in the past
decade. Samuel, a minister of the Ethiopian church and Inkatha leader in
Patheni, recalls that the violence began with non-political faction-fighting
in the early 1980s - and escalated after Nelson Mandela, the ANC leader, was
released from prison of in 1990.
Samuel gestures at Nkosi Dhlamini, the hereditary chief of the Patheni area,
who sits silently at the side of a room in Patheni's tribal court building.
It is one of the few modern structures in a village which lacks electricity
and internal plumbing and which could have been transplanted straight from
19th century Zululand. Samuel says the troubles started when the youth of
Patheni ridiculed the chief, ignored his authority and insisted he leave the
KwaZulu homeland (which pays him a salary as chief) to join the ANC-aligned
Congress of Traditional Leaders of South Africa. Njilo points out the
bracelet of goat's hair worn by Dhlamini as a mark of office: 'They looked
at Dhlamini and laughed and said: 'look at this man]' They are not Zulus any
more. They are rejecting their tradition,' he says angrily. The strict
discipline of Zulu society decrees that youth must obey age and that the
word of the chief and his headmen is law, in all but the most serious
criminal cases.
Samuel says tradition is the crux of the dispute between the ANC and IFP.
'All those Zulus (who support the ANC), they are not proper Zulus, they are
imitation, imitation, they are too weak,' he says, jumping up to demonstrate
the proper walk for a Zulu man wearing the traditional 'beshu', or skin
skirt worn on feast days: 'Raise yourself. Everyone must see: this is a man.
Look at his culture,' he roars, with that combination of machismo and pride
which makes it so easy to offend IFP members, and so hard to placate them.
'Chief Albert Luthuli (a former ANC president, a Nobel peace prize winner
and a Zulu), if he was still living, I don't think there would be IFP in
this country. He was a man,' says Samuel, adding that Mandela, a member of
the Xhosa tribe which he despises for being insufficiently warlike, is being
'used' by the ANC.
After Mandela's release the youth of both villages confronted their chiefs,
putting a burning tyre (the famous 'necklace') around the neck of the
Ndaleni chief, who fled. Many died in the ensuing fighting. Marauding
parties from both villages came over the hill at night to murder opponents.
In the end the young people from Patheni who supported the United Democratic
Front (forerunner to the ANC) fled to Ndaleni, leaving one quarter of
Patheni's houses empty; IFP sympathisers from Ndaleni took refuge in
Patheni. The politically committed in both villages were a minority; but the
apolitical majority threw in their lot with the activists; they could hardly
do otherwise.
Since that time, Samuel and Joseph - who grew up as brothers in the same
household, and experienced the same rites of passage to Zulu manhood - have
not seen one another. When we offered to set up a meeting at a neutral spot,
outside the area, both were suspicious; perhaps they thought that we, or our
Zulu guide, planned to arrange an assassination.
'I am crying to see him. It's my family,' says Samuel of Joseph. 'It's only
our organisation makes us fight each other, for nothing. When my brothers
die other side, I can't even attend the funeral.'
Samuel is far more of a politician than Joseph, who only recently joined the
ANC, and then - he says - only because 'all the residents of this area are
ANC members.' Samuel joined the ANC in 1958, but when the organisation was
banned in 1960, he opted not to join the movement in exile. 'We couldn't
just go all of us into exile,' he says. When Inkatha was launched in 1975 -
it was intended to operate as a kind of internal wing for the banned ANC -
he joined. The two movements parted ways when the Inkatha leader, Chief
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, fell out with the ANC leadership. After some
soul-searching, Samuel stuck with Buthelezi.
As a result, Samuel's house at Folweni, a township near Durban, was burned
and his furniture destroyed by ANC supporters. He explains this as he
apologises for the primitive condition of his house at Patheni, part-ruin
and part traditional thatched hut, with a stand of blood-red dahlias in the
dirt yard outside. As areas near Durban have fallen to the ANC, many IFP
supporters have had to do as Samuel has done, and return to the deep rural
areas which are IFP strongholds.
Now these areas are preparing to boycott April's all-race elections. 'They
(the ANC) must accept what we want. We can't just vote for nothing. We are
not so stupid,' says Samuel, displaying the wounded pride which is perhaps
the greatest hallmarks of Inkatha. He says he does not know what Patheni
will do, but he will not vote; it seems a fair bet that his neighbours will
not dare to defy his lead.
Across the hill at Ndaleni, Catherine Njilo, Joseph's wife, sits at her
kitchen table, peering at us by the light of a flickering candle, as gusts
of wind blow in from the rainy night. She asks: 'Can grannies vote?' We
assure her that they can. Still, she says, it is not wise for all the
members of a family to vote. Her daughters help with an explanation: 'If
there are 10 members of the family then you mustn't all vote because you may
vote for different parties, and then you will quarrel.' Her teenage son
argues that a vote for Mandela is a vote for a new house; since eight adults
and two grandchildren live in this tiny space, without any salary, his
argument may prove persuasive.
Will Joseph vote? Like many Zulus, he will not answer such questions from
whites. If he does, he says, he is not worried that the ANC will fail to
protect Zulu tradition. 'Zululand is for Zulus, and Transkei is for Xhosas.
Even after the elections, Zululand will be for Zulus]' he says,
demonstrating how little he has understood the ANC's policy of
non-racialism, which denies such tribal divisions. His face in the
candlelight, marked by deep tribal scarring, is the face of a man who is
every bit as traditional as his brother Samuel. But fate and geography have
divided them, perhaps forever. The elections may only make matters worse.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page I
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-16517</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EDJAAAC5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940409
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Long View: Shares under pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A first quarter setback for the London stock market is seasonally quite
unusual, and can be blamed on overseas events, notably the upsets in
international bonds. Plainly, though, UK equities were looking expensive at
the end of last year.
I described them here as being 'only for the brave and nimble' although the
flood tide of global liquidity might yet carry them to a dividend yield of 3
per cent. In the event the All-Share Index rose another 5 per cent to a peak
on February 2, and the yield fell to a scant 3.2 per cent. Then, like so
many other securities markets, the London stock market was spooked by the US
Federal Reserve's initial quarter-point increase in dollar short-term
interest rates on February 4.
The international origin of London's setback is evident from the behaviour
of the different indices. The market leaders which comprise the FTSE-100
Index were down 10 per cent in the three months (and by 12 1/2 per cent from
the peak) but the All-Share was off only 7 per cent and the SmallCap Index
was in fact marginally higher.
Even now the average dividend yield on the SmallCap constituents is under 3
per cent, while Footsie stocks yield 3.9 per cent. Overseas holders of blue
chips have been selling, but the mainly domestic holders of second-liners
have not budged.
Much more violent events have been taking place in bonds, where long gilts,
for instance, started the year on a freakishly low yield of 6.37 per cent,
which has subsequently jumped (by about 1 1/2 percentage points at the
worst). In US Treasury bonds, where all the trouble really started, the
benchmark 30-year issue lost about 13 per cent of its capital value in the
first quarter, greatly underperforming US equities (down only about 4 per
cent).
Although some analysts are claiming that this bond market collapse implies a
rise in expectations of inflation, I believe this is a false conclusion. We
have simply witnessed the collapse of a speculative bubble. It appears to
have been very much of a bond market version of the equity market boom and
crash in 1987. That was interpreted in some quarters as heralding a new
Great Depression, but nothing on that scale has happened. Similarly, the
problems of the bond market have little economic consequence in themselves,
except to illustrate the proneness of the modern financial system to
speculative excesses - which appear to be transferring to the commodities
markets.
The bond bubble had the effect of distorting the relationships between bonds
and equities. In the UK this has been further complicated by the presence of
index-linked gilts, so that there is a real long-term interest rate (at
present about 3.4 per cent) in the market as well as a fixed interest rate
(7.7 per cent) and an equity dividend yield (3.7 per cent on the All-Share).
Market strategists attempt to fit these into a kind of matrix to allow for
inflation and dividend growth, plus margins for risk.
By the end of last year the low fixed-interest yield was putting heavy
downward pressure on the index-linked real yield. Meanwhile room was created
for equities to rise despite the poor value they represented on fundamental
grounds of dividends and earnings.
The subsequent jump in the real yield on index-linkers has in effect forced
equity yields up, because risky shares have to yield significantly more than
safe gilts (unless there are exceptional prospects for short-term dividend
growth). True, index-linked gilts only have about 5 per cent of the market
value of equities, so you might say that the tail is improbably wagging the
dog; but the London equity market has always been highly yield-conscious by
international standards.
Meanwhile the equity yield has also been tugged upwards by fixed interest
yields, to maintain a yield ratio of about 2. This was a common ratio during
the 1980s, but as I have written before, it has varied widely over the
longer term (being under 1 until the late 1950s) and is also very different
in other countries.
To justify a ratio of around 2 you need to assume moderately high inflation
as well as decent economic growth. If inflation stays low, as on balance I
believe it will, the ratio will surely have to fall: I would be happier with
a figure of about 1.5 or 1.6. If inflation rises sharply share prices will
fall anyway, as both short and long interest rates jump.
If anything UK economic expansion has been looking too hot for the equity
market's comfort recently; the best hope now is that the tax increases which
have just taken effect will cool this growth. If not, the lack of balance in
the upturn - too much consumer spending, too little investment - will lead
to a typical UK balance of payments crisis.
The economic statistics are of such poor quality that it is impossible to be
confident of what is going on. But. as far as the corporate sector is
concerned, profit and dividend growth almost appears too buoyant, so that in
the water sector, for instance, a political backlash is beginning to
develop. If the economy slows a sterling crisis may be avoided but investors
may feelthat they have become complacent about profits growth over the next
year or two.
Plainly, share prices in the UK offer rather better value now than they did
at the beginning of the year. The prospective yield on the market leaders,
allowing for dividend rises in the rest of the results season, is probably
around 4 per cent.
We are approaching that period of the year, however, when seasonal pressures
are more more regularly negative. We have not seen a full unwinding yet of
the phase of overvaluation that began to develop, along with the bond market
bubble, in the third quarter of last year.
But prepare your buying list anyway. Reasonable value may not now be too far
away, perhaps created by a political scare or two.
</TEXT>
