<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Surge in sales of new vehicles underpins strength of
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A larger-than-expected surge in sales in virtually all sectors of the new
vehicle market should underpin hopes that the recovery is still on course.
Figures released yesterday by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders
show that new-car registrations were up by 14.8 per cent in March on a
year-on-year basis. New registrations in the commercial vehicle sector leapt
by 28 per cent.
The scale of the improvement in the commercial vehicle market may silence
some sceptics in the motor industry who have maintained that the strength of
the recovery is being over-stated. They fear a false impression was being
created by marketing techniques to attract reluctant private buyers, and by
some manufacturers encouraging dealers to register many cars for which there
were no final buyers. Commercial vehicle sales are made for purely business
reasons, and are a good market indicator.
Sales of vans, trucks and buses increased last month to 22,648 compared with
17,741 at the same time last year. The increase, the third consecutive month
of rises, brings commercial registrations for the first quarter to 56,602,
12.65 per cent up on the first quarter last year.
Sales of new cars last month rose to 185,201, compared with 161,338 in the
same month last year. They lifted registrations for the first quarter of the
year to 529,436 from 453,261 at the same time last year.
This represents a 16.81 per cent rise for the quarter, and seems to indicate
that the car market slowed in March. However, January was an artificially
good month with its year-on-year rise of 20 per cent after poor sales the
previous January.
Mr Ernie Thompson, chief executive of the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders, said: 'These figures clearly indicate that the recovery is being
maintained despite the widespread knowledge of pending tax increases and
changes in company car tax benefit assessment.'
The new tax regime for company cars, based on a percentage of list prices,
came into effect on April 6.
Yesterday's figures suggest the society's forecast of 1.9m new-car sales
this year, compared with 1.78m in 1993, may be pessimistic.
The share of last month's car market taken by imports rose to 57.9 per cent
from 55 per cent in March last year.
Vehicle sales table, Page 5
</TEXT>
