<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Brussels' lobbyists go back to school to learn art of charm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dogged by a public relations image that they admit is lamentable, Brussels'
lobbyists will soon have the chance to learn new skills at a charm school of
their own.
The first professional course aimed at providing practical training for
lobbying European institutions is to be opened later this month in Brussels
by the European Institute of Public Affairs and Lobbying, which is devoted
to teaching the tricks of the campaigning trade.
The aims of the 13-week course, the organisers say, is to instil some badly
needed US-style 'professionalism' into Europe's rapidly growing army of
pressure groups - a sector that is now believed to employ about 10,000
people in Brussels alone, after more than doubling in the past four years.
'A lot of people believe that to be a good lobbyist all you need is a good
address book - but it's a lot more than that. It is a professional skill and
job,' says Mr Daniel Gueguen, a course leader and seasoned campaigner for
Europe's sugar industry.
But with the lobbyists' rise provoking alarm in some commission quarters,
the creation of a special course on campaigning is likely to beg new
questions about the lack of regulation of Europe's pressure groups.
Later this month a committee of the European Parliament is due to consider
proposals that Europe's lobbyists should be forced to register and operate
under a formal code of conduct.
The author of the proposal, Mr Alman Metten, a Dutch MEP, insists regulation
is needed to 'prevent the type of abuses' he claims have become more
widespread as the sector has grown.
But the proposal has been criticised by the lobbyists themselves, who argue
that regulation would merely create a new level of bureaucracy in a city
already over-burdened by red tape.
Either way, all sides agree that the army of lobbyists could soon be
reaching US proportions. However, the lobbyists admit that US-style tactics
are unlikely to work in Europe, particularly when faced with the more subtle
political style favoured by France and the southern countries of Europe.
Mr Gilbert Portal, of the petroleum industry lobby, says: 'The European
style is less aggressive than the US. You cannot attack a French MEP in the
same way as you can in Washington.'
</TEXT>
