<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / The Lex Column: Queens Moat Houses
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The encouraging message in yesterday's results from Queens Moat Houses is
that the new management has made a good start in getting to grips with the
operational side of the business. The discouraging part is that there is
still such a long way to go. After so many different valuations have been
applied to its hotel portfolio one must take any figure with a pinch of
salt. The latest one puts Queens Moat's better hotels broadly on a level
with industry norms in terms of valuation per room. But the operating return
on the revalued assets is a mere 2 per cent and, at Pounds 18m, operating
profits pale into insignificance compared with an interest bill of Pounds
110m.
Queens Moat has long been candid in admitting that it cannot hope to
generate enough cash to service its existing debt. The question is how much
debt it could reasonably carry after its financial restructuring. There are
still considerable benefits to flow from cost savings and more active
marketing. That will come on top of any cyclical recovery in the hotel
business. So profits, at least in the UK, could grow quite strongly.
But even if Queens Moat managed to push its margin on continuing operations
up to 20 per cent from 7 at present it would still have operating profits of
little more than Pounds 60m. Allowing a tight interest cover ratio of two
times that would be sufficient to service less than a third of the present
Pounds 1.2bn debt. The restructuring still promises to be painful, despite
the improved trading climate.
</TEXT>
