<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / The Lex Column: Utilities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the first of British Gas's businesses to feel the heat of competition
is its high street chain, which is being cut almost in half to 240 shops.
The division aims to become a pure appliance retailer, in direct competition
with other household goods shops. It does not intend to perform services for
other parts of the group.
Whether British Gas can ever make an acceptable return in the fiercely
competitive world of appliance retailing is a moot point. On a fully costed
basis the chain probably loses money at present. Out-of-town competitors may
well offer larger ranges and lower prices. Gas's attitude is also in marked
contrast to other utilities - notably some regional electricity companies
and BT - which are expanding their chains. They argue that intangible
benefits justify running the stores even if they lose money. The water
companies have hardly bothered to be in the high street at all.
Retailing is unlikely to prove a sensible business for utilities. Even
experienced specialists struggle to make money in hardware sales and many
other providers of services are looking away from the high street. Banking
and insurance, for example, are increasingly done by telephone. Direct Line
and First Direct's brands are strengthening as a result. It is particularly
ironic that BT, one of the first companies into the virtual world of
computerised networks, should feel the need for a high street presence.
Smallish losses may mean that shareholders do not object, but flagships on
the high street add little value.
</TEXT>
