<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Prudential boost
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The life assurance sector included a number of strong performers, notably
Prudential, up 3 at 320p and Legal &amp; General, up 8 at 473p. The latter were
boosted by the recent recommendation from BZW, which rates the stock as its
favourite in a sector offering a generous 35 per cent yield premium to the
market and superior dividend prospects.
Prudential's shares were principally driven by a recommendation from Hoare
Govett who said the stock had suffered too much from investor worries about
tighter regulation, alleged mis-selling of personal pensions and rather
disappointing 1993 new business figures. Hoare said investors should focus
instead on above-average dividend prospects following the cost-reduction
programme, the re-shaping of the group's UK field force and strong growth in
sales via intermediaries. 'The prospective yield of 5.7 per cent is
unwarranted for a company that has grown its dividend since 1980 twice as
fast as that of the average British company,' Hoare concluded.
Shell Transport, which has lagged behind BP in the general upsurge in oil
shares over the past week or so, outpaced the latter as a more positive view
of the stock uncovered a stock shortage among London's marketmakers.
At the close Shell, were 14 higher at 696p, having reached 699p earlier in
the session. UBS, the stockbroker, was said to have upgraded its Shell
forecast and triggered the early demand. SG Warburg was also positive on the
sector.
BP gained 2 to 373p but Burmah Castrol, reporting on Monday, slipped 11 to
815p. Enterprise was the pick of the exploration and production stocks,
advancing 11 more to 439p.
A big bought deal in Spring Ram, the bathrooms and kitchens group, left the
company the heaviest traded stock on the London market with more than 63m
shares changing hands.
Shortly after the market closed it was announced that Lazard Freres Asset
Management had sold 34.2m Spring Ram shares, made up of 29.4m 'old' shares
and the rest in 'new' stock from the rights issue. The 29.4m was sold to BZW
at 55 3/4 p and placed by the investment bank at 56 1/2 p.
Kleinwort Benson was said to have been largely responsible for the good
showing by Whitbread, which outperformed the sector to close 6 higher at
523p. Kleinwort said it expected a substantial re-rating to accompany
Whitbread's results in May. Recent disposals have left Whitbread with the
strongest balance sheet, healthiest free cash flow and best earnings growth
potential of the big brewers, according to the broker.
Board room changes at components company Laird Group, which also reported an
increase in both profits and the dividend sent the shares soaring 19 to
388p. Mr Sandy Morris at NatWest Securities believes it to be 'the best
quality stock in the sector.'
Industrial engineering group Triplex Lloyd tumbled after warning of a Pounds
3m loss for the year to March 1994. The shares were down 18 at worst before
steadying to finish 13 lower at 133p.
Broker recommendations made earlier in the week continued to help GKN and
the shares added another 4 to 580p.
Early weakness in New York imposed pressure on internationally traded stocks
with hard-hit Glaxo slipping 9 to 604p on turnover of 5.2m after some heavy
institutional selling by one US house, Reuters Holdings shedding 22 to 1927p
and Zeneca easing 4 to 729p. SmithKline Beecham lost 5 at 370p in the 'A's
in spite of positive news on its drug pipeline.
Pharmaceuticals group Wellcome rebounded from earlier falls as analysts
decided that the full text of the Anglo-French Concorde study on AZT carried
no new damaging information bout the anti-Aids treatment. The company
insisted the full report showed that AZT did delay the onset of AIDS in
symptom free adults. The shares, 11 down at worst closed 2 off at 555p.
Turnover in business services group BET rose to 8m and the shares shed 5 to
120p, after James Capel was reported to have downgraded profit expectations.
Conglomerate Trafalgar House's ordinary shares closed 4 ahead at 104p as
Robert Fleming highlighted the attractions of the convertible stock. Mr
Robert Gibson at the broker said: 'They offer a relatively risk free 6 per
cent yield with only a small premium over the ordinary stock.' The
convertible shares gained 6 1/4 to 132 1/4 p.
</TEXT>
