<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture (Week in the Markets): Funds
drive up coffee futures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London robusta coffee futures were driven to fresh four-year highs this week
as investment fund buyers latched on to growing concerns about nearby
availability. But dealers were well aware that the speculative nature of the
rise meant that the bubble could burst at any moment.
The market peaked on Thursday, when the July delivery position reached
Dollars 1,450 a tonne. By yesterday's close it had eased to Dollars 1,436,
up Dollars 73 on the week.
Buyers were encouraged by rumours that the Ivory Coast might halt coffee and
cocoa exports unless shippers paid a back-dated export tax. And the advance
was underpinned by a report from London broker ED &amp; F. Man warning that
consumer stocks of robusta coffee - the coarser type grown mainly in Africa
 -had become uncomfortably low, reflecting the success of the export
retention scheme producers have been operating since October. At the end of
February these stocks stood at 16.9m bags (60kg each), down 3.3m from a year
earlier, Man estimat-ed.
Apart from driving prices higher across the board, supply worries resulted
in the establishment this week of a sizeable premium, or 'backwardation',
for the prompt May delivery position at the London Commodity Exchange. At
yesterday's close the premium stood at Dollars 21 a tonne over the July
contract, which a week earlier had itself been commanding a Dollars 3
premium.
At the London Metal Exchange the recent shake-out in copper prices continued
until support was found late in the week. The three months position, which
had touched Dollars 1,873 a tonne at one stage, closed yesterday at Dollars
1,889.25, up Dollars 1 on balance. There was disappointment, however, that
news of another sharp drawdown from LME warehouse stocks had not enabled the
contract to regain its foothold above Dollars 1,900.
In contrast the aluminium market seemed to take great comfort yesterday from
a second consecutive stocks cut that took the drawdown over the week to
11,525 tonnes. Talk of possible output reductions by producers in the Urals,
where power cuts are planned, gave further encouragement to buyers and the
three months price gained Dollars 19 on the day to close at Dollars 1,319.50
a tonne. That represented a net gain of Dollars 5 on the week and was
Dollars 30.50 above the low point reached on Thursday morning.
Thursday had also seen the low for lead, which touched a four-month low of
Dollars 435 a tonne in the three months position. But investors then decided
that the markets fundamentals did not justify such a low price and by
yesterday's close it was back at Dollars 452.75 a tonne, down a relatively
modest Dollars 5 on the week.
The oil market was also defying fundamentals this week, according to some
analysts. An investment fund-driven price jump in New York on Monday, was
echoed at London's International Petroleum Exchange on Tuesday when traders
returned after the Easter holiday. North Sea Brent crude prices were quickly
into the heady regions above Dollars 14 a barrel and, to the surprise of
many observers, held most of their gains for the rest of the week.
The only explanation most analysts could offer was that the market was
suffering from a 'guilt syndrome' after over-reacting on the downside to the
failure of the Organisation of Oil Producing Countries to agree on a
reduction in its output ceiling at its recent ministerial meeting.
