FT  09 APR 94 / International Company News: Santana Motor to put viability
scheme to unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Suzuki's struggling Spanish subsidiary Santana Motor will present its
viability plan to unions and the Andalusian government on Monday, Reuter
reports from Madrid.
The meeting will centre on Suzuki's proposal to shed two thirds of the
workforce to keep the southern Spanish plant going. The company wants its
workers to agree to the plan, and the regional government to help with a
capital injection.
Workers, 2,000 of whom have been temporarily laid off, have blocked the
factory gates at Linares for nearly two months.
Suzuki says it cannot pay April salaries unless they let out some of the
plant's finished vehicles.
