<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / International Company News: Dresdner Bank confident on
current-year profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Profits at Dresdner Bank are continuing to increase after a 24 per cent
surge to DM2.04bn (Dollars 1.19bn) in operating earnings last year, Mr
Jurgen Sarrazin, group chairman, said yesterday.
Reporting a double-digit rise in income for the first two months, he
forecast a satisfactory result for the full year after an 'especially
successful' 1993.
Mr Sarrazin also announced plans for a more international distribution of
the group's shares. As expected, he unveiled a project to raise an estimated
DM1.2bn through a private placing of American depositary receipts with US
institutions.
Dresdner was the first German bank to take this route, which did not oblige
it to adopt more transparent US accounting and reporting practices, he said.
The new paper would be priced at around the current share price, he added.
Shareholders would also be asked at the annual meeting on May 20 to approve
a further DM200m authorised capital to be issued as convertible bonds or
options by the bank's foreign subsidiaries.
In common with other domestic banks, Dresdner markedly increased provisions
against bad debts last year: a 47 per cent increase took the total to
DM1.77bn. The bank had been severely affected by the DM3.4bn rescue of
Metallgesellschaft, but all provisions and costs had been included in the
1993 results, Mr Sarrazin said.
Following the rescue Dresdner's stake in the metals, mining and engineering
group had risen to 14 per cent from 12.6 per cent.
Reviewing prospects for the current year, Mr Sarrazin said he expected
developments to be 'calm'. Demand for financing for exports and construction
would rise more strongly, with a more modest increase in calls for
investment loans from corporate customers.
He hoped increased industrial production would expand, increasing plant
utilisation rates and helping restore domestic customers' financial
stability. This would enable the bank to scale down risk-provisioning in the
current year.
Personal business would suffer because falling real incomes would lead to
lower savings and less demand for loans for large purchases. While he did
not expect an absolute decline in this area, growth rates would certainly
shrink.
Mr Sarrazin also expected own-account trading to continue to improve on the
back of rising German stock markets, although he indicated that developments
would be less dramatic than in 1993. Last year's profits from financial
transactions increased 122 per cent to DM650m.
Net commission income rose 29 per cent to DM3.16bn, interest earnings
increased 9.6 per cent to DM6.27bn, and pre-tax profits climbed 17 per cent
to DM1.83bn.
As announced earlier this week, the 1993 dividend was raised DM1.50 to
DM13.50.
