FT  09 APR 94 / International Company News: Lenzing to cut payout after
posting deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Lenzing, the world's leading producer of viscose fibre, yesterday reported
higher sales for 1993 but will post a Sch203.1m (Dollars 16.8m) deficit due
to extraordinary losses at its Glanzstoff unit.
Sales for the group, which has production facilities in the US, Indonesia,
Brazil and Austria, rose 9.5 per cent to Sch8.74bn (Dollars 740m) from
Sch7.98bn in 1992. Profits from ordinary business, including tax on income,
was Sch115.4m, but it will post a net deficit because the losses at the
Glanzstoff plant.
The management board is proposing to cut the dividend to Sch5 a share from
Sch16.
The Glanzstoff subsidiary was badly hit by the downturn in the European
motor industry, which caused a sharp decline in orders for viscose tyre
reinforcing materials during the second half of last year. Production will
be closed down later this year, and the site sold or rented. As a result of
the necessary write-offs Glanzstoff posted a net loss of Sch396.9m.
Sales at Lenzing Austria were little changed at Sch3.2bn, though sales
improved at the main subsidiaries. Lenzing's US unit increased its market
share to more than 40 per cent with sales of Sch1.4bn.
