<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / UK Company News - The AGM Season: Anxieties, butterflies and
parachute jumping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Christopher Hogg, chairman of Reuters and a veteran of annual meetings,
likens AGMs to jumping from a plane. 'When you have done it and landed, then
it is no problem, but every time might be the last,' the former parachutist
says.
Some might think Sir Christopher has less cause to feel anxious than many
others who face shareholders every year. Yet even he finds AGMs 'slightly
anxious' occasions. 'There is a vaguely confrontational feel about the
thing,' he says.
The butterflies are common, although in some cases they may be described
rather differently. 'I love AGMs, I really love them,' says Mr David James,
the company doctor and chairman of Lep who makes a habit of taking on posts
where the AGMs are inevitably confrontational. 'They are great adrenalin
developers.'
Most chairmen will spend a considerable amount of time preparing for the
meetings. Sir Christopher's schedule calls for a detailed examination of the
report and accounts, all the press announcements made during the year, and a
review of the letters sent in by shareholders. Mr James demands a dress
rehearsal at his companies, which include the board, financial advisers and
lawyers.
Yet no company can prepare for the variety of questions which may be thrown
at the board. At Barclays, one shareholder demanded to know why there had
not been enough Easter eggs to pass out to all the customers waiting in the
queue at his local branch. The eggs ran out just before they got to him.
Such questions often seem to dominate AGMs, leaving many chairmen with the
private belief that the meetings accomplish little. 'Often the questions
that are asked are not the important ones which face the business,' says one
chairman of a struggling company. 'They are about trivia.'
The fact that institutions seem to share this sentiment almost ensures that
in many cases the main issues receive scant attention. 'If they would come
and ask about the really important issues that face a company, that would
create a better balanced meeting,' the chairman says.
There are some companies where shareholders never ask questions, such as at
the shoe company Fii where the formal part of the AGM rarely lasts more than
15 minutes. In fact, shareholders have been known to bring stop-watches to
the meetings to see whether the chairman, Mr Monty Sumray, can beat his
record time of less than two minutes.
Publicly and privately, almost all chairmen will say that AGMs are an
important part of corporate governance.
'Shareholders should have the right to question directors providing they use
the AGM to ask about the company and not for political matters,' says Mr
Andrew Buxton of Barclays. 'It gives them a way of voicing their concerns.'
For many, the most useful part of the meeting is when the business is
concluded, and shareholders seek out the board personally.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
