<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / UK Company News - The AGM Season: Where attendance levels
focus on the freebies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Diverting corporate history is not always uppermost in the minds of those
regular attenders of annual meetings. As one seasoned organiser said: 'The
bulk are there for the love of the sound of their own voice, or a free
sandwich.'
The AGM is like a class reunion, particularly for the retired employees who
attend. While there may be colourful speeches and aggressive questioning,
the emphasis remains primarily on presentation and consumption.
In some cases, the actual purpose is lost. One listed company had large
attendances for several years, attracted by a buffet and drinks. But last
year, directors were faced with an almost empty auditorium, after the
registrars decided to check on arrivals and found that genuine shareholders
were a significant minority.
'You can usually gauge the attendance level of an AGM by the size of the
lunch or the gifts', said one cynical PR executive.
However, there are changes afoot. The recession has affected the quality of
free gifts, such as key rings and pens, at the same time as it has hit
corporate confidence. In post-Cadbury Britain, shareholders are therefore
taking the formal portion of the meeting more seriously.
Troubled industrial giants, such as British Aerospace and Trafalgar House,
have attracted crowds out of proportion to their hospitality, reflecting
concern over chequered management performance.
'The question and answer sessions are getting longer, and while AGM's are
getting more stagey, there are fewer shareholders coming along just for the
vol-au-vents and Chablis,' said Mr Stuart Bell, research director at
Pensions and Investment Research Consultants.
Shareholders at the recent Lonrho and BAe AGM's managed to lead a vociferous
and coherent opposition to management policy.
But since the power of small shareholders is limited - proxy votes vastly
outstripped attempted people power at Lonrho and BAe - such drama is
generally only the icing, and attention is more focused on the quality of
the cake.
For these regulars, 60 seconds on the microphone, a glass of wine, and a
gift of a pen or a food pack, must remain sufficient justification for their
annual trip to the corporate pantomime.
Food and drink-related companies therefore remain the traditional
crowd-pullers. Guinness, for example, has created a popular formula of
plenty of good food, followed by a pack of goodies in a black velvet bag.
At last year's Tomkins AGM, the mass of shareholders were less inclined to
question management on its running of the Ranks Hovis McDougall business,
and more focused on Ranks' legendary annual gift packs.
The true test for the cynics will be the Tomkins turn-out in September. The
company decided last year that it should be delivering earnings per share
rather than RHM hand-out's, and it gave out nothing. It is quite possible
that the smaller shareholders will disagree.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
