<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / UK Company News: Regina's warring sides call for help
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Things are buzzing at Regina, the USM-quoted royal jelly maker that has
numbered Lady Thatcher, Dame Barbara Cartland, Cliff Richard and Millwall
Football Club among its customers.
Mr Shiraz Malik-Noor, the former chairman and chief executive who was hived
off in a coup last month, has requisitioned an extraordinary meeting on
April 25 to get himself reappointed to the board.
Mr Malik-Noor remains the largest shareholder, with 5.4 per cent of the
company. Croxley Holdings, his family trust, has 18.9 per cent.
Yesterday the current board - comprising Mr Paul Geoghegan, chairman, and Mr
Tony Shakesby, finance director - sent a stinging letter to the company's
shareholders urging them to oppose Mr Malik-Noor's reappointment.
The letter points out to more than 4,000 shareholders that the company has
notched up cumulative losses of more than Pounds 1.4m in the past two
financial years. Mr Malik-Noor's salary, his sister's salary and other
benefits and expenses have reached Pounds 450,000 since he joined the
company in early 1991.
Sales fell by 60 per cent to Pounds 2.05m for the year to end-August 1993,
and have continued to decline in the first half.
Mr Geoghegan said at the company's Finchley head office that he had every
confidence of winning at the EGM, judging from telephone calls.
However, Mr Malik-Noor is expecting the support not only of his family
trust, but of a further 15 per cent held by friends and supporters, giving
him about 40 per cent.
'I don't feel I can fold my tent and just walk away,' he said yesterday. He
pointed out that he and associates had put more than Pounds 1.5m into the
company in the last three years.
Mr Geoghegan blames the falling sales on 'inappropriate marketing
expenditure to support the brand'.
</TEXT>
