FT  09 APR 94 / UK Company News: Torday &amp; Carlisle cuts loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Torday &amp; Carlisle, the Newcastle-based engineer, cut its pre-tax loss from
Pounds 15.1m to Pounds 292,000 for 1993.
The loss was struck after an exceptional profit of Pounds 3.02m on the
disposal of Elfab Hughes, which makes pressure relief and safety equipment,
and exceptional costs of Pounds 2.96m (Pounds 5.28m). The loss for 1992
included a provision of Pounds 8.21m against goodwill at Oldham Signs.
Elfab contributed operating profits of Pounds 544,000 for the 11 months
before the sale.
Operating profits from continuing businesses were Pounds 35,000, compared
with a previous loss of Pounds 1.45m.
Turnover from continuing businesses fell from Pounds 34.1m to Pounds 28.8m.
Total group turnover was Pounds 32.7m (Pounds 38.9m).
The exceptional costs include Pounds 963,000 for environmental controls in
the Netherlands.
Borrowings were down from Pounds 7.77m to Pounds 5.2m, giving gearing of 73
per cent (109 per cent).
Earnings were 0.2p against losses of 93p.
