<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Almost a law unto themselves: A look at the work of the US
Supreme Court, where a vacancy has arisen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is never easy to get a seat to watch the US Supreme Court at work. Two
Mondays ago, the galleries were packed with the likes of Howard Davies, head
of the Confederation of British Industry, as the world's most celebrated
bench assembled to hear oral arguments on one of the biggest cases on its
calendar this year - which happened, unusually, to involve a foreign
company, Barclays Bank, in its case against California's system of unitary
taxation.
The mood was not entirely one of reverence. It took the marshal's whistle to
silence the veteran court watchers making a book on which justice would be
first to interrupt counsel, who are given precisely 22 1/2 minutes to argue
their cases. The court marched in, the nine Justices taking their seats in
order of seniority on either side of Chief Justice William Rehnquist,
presenting an arc of styles, mannerisms and convictions.
It was the mild-mannered Justice David Souter who scooped the pool,
confounding the heavy odds on the voluble Justice Antonin Scalia, who
invariably spouts Latin and discourses on Alexander Hamilton's Federalist
Papers. The diminutive Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, the court's newest
member, sat bolt upright on Mr Rehnquist's far left and peppered the lawyers
with questions, interrupting, and thus annoying, some more senior
colleagues, including the other woman justice, the courteous Sandra Day
O'Connor.
At the other end of the row, Justice Clarence Thomas, eighth in precedence
and the only black, sat back and rocked gently, his booming voice never
heard. Unusually silent on this occasion was the oldest member, 85-year-old
Harry Blackmun, but he, perhaps, had something else on his mind.
On Wednesday, the country discovered what that was, as Blackmun, one of two
remaining liberals on the bench, announced he was retiring after 24 years
marked by a crusty independence, mostly in the minority. It was,
comfortably, the biggest US story of the week, as it invariably is when a
justice steps down.
The Supreme Court remains an abiding fascination, both because of what it
is, the third and equal pillar of the US government along with the
presidency and Congress, and because the greatest of its 110 names -
Marshall, Harlan, Frankfurter, Holmes, Brandeis, Warren, Black - are
embedded in US history. Appointed for life, and often serving into their
80s, justices can help shape the nation long beyond the times and political
circumstances of their appointments. William O Douglas was named by FDR in
1939 because he was an expert on financial regulation. But in 36 years on
the court he rarely faced such a case and was free to develop his trenchant
liberalism.
Even when they do retire, some justices remain around the court in offices
provided for them, wielding influence behind the scenes. Chief Justice
Rehnquist, a conservative, is sometimes said to be near apoplectic at the
way Justice William Brennan (1956-90) still insinuates his eloquent liberal
arguments over morning coffee with the likes of Justice Souter, a Bush
appointee.
Many of the court's judgments have had monumental impact. Dred Scott (1857)
legitimised slavery and thus, in the eyes of the South, the civil war;
Plessy (1896) upheld public segregation by race; Brown (1954) undid Plessy,
and made the reputation of Thurgood Marshall, later the court's first black
member; Miranda (1966) established rights for criminal suspects and changed
the way the police went about their business; Roe (1973), associated, if not
entirely accurately, with Justice Blackmun, protected women's right to
abortion.
Given all this, it is hardly surprising that every president slavers at the
opportunity to shape the court. Bill Clinton was unfairly criticised last
year because he took 85 days to name a replacement for the retiring Justice
Byron White. His selection process might have been messy but the mere
prospect of being the first Democratic president since 1967 able to appoint
a justice was enough to militate against haste. In the event, the popular
Ginsburg nomination proved a turning point in Mr Clinton's sagging fortunes
last summer.
Similarly, court nominees, subject to confirmation by the Senate, often
prompt serious opposition, irrespective of the popularity of the president.
Messrs Reagan and Bush each lost a candidate, Mr Nixon lost two in a year,
and Mr Johnson could not elevate Justice Abe Fortas to the Chief's position.
In each instance, ideological objections, plus reservations about legal
competence and other issues, were decisive.
As a rough rule, Republican presidents have tended to name conservative
judges to the court, on the assumption that they will stick to the limited
letter of the constitution and roll back the frontiers of federal power.
Democrats, with fewer recent chances, have naturally preferred the reverse
and also shown more partiality to practising politicians, as witnessed by Mr
Clinton's current interest in Senator George Mitchell from Maine.
The glittering exception was President Eisenhower's appointment of Earl
Warren, the Republican governor of California, to be Chief Justice in 1953.
Mr Warren's subsequent direction of the most activist liberal court this
century, starting with the Brown ruling, prompted Ike to confess it was the
'worst appointment I have ever made'. He later added Justice Brennan, whom
he named just before the 1956 election simply to shore up the Irish Catholic
vote, to his list.
Justices are frequently unpredictable once on the bench. President Nixon
thought Mr Blackmun a safe conservative and was proved wrong, while Justice
White, a Kennedy nominee, moved increasingly to the right. Of the present
court, all Republican appointments except Justice Ginsburg, only Messrs
Rehnquist, Scalia and Thomas have consistently lived up to conservative
expectations. They do not constitute a majority, which explains why the
Reagan revolution, including repealing the Roe ruling, ultimately languished
at the highest judicial level.
The court does go through phases of activism followed by consolidation,
often contra-cyclical to the prevailing political mood. The present bench
has the reputation for not breaking much new ground. Perhaps aware of its
own internal fault lines, it has tended to choose cases for judgment mostly
of a dry, technical nature, though many may have wider subsequent
implications, especially in the area of workplace law.
On controversial cases, such as last year's judgment on Pennsylvania's more
restrictive abortion laws, it offered so many opinions that Justice O'Connor
confessed she had no idea what the court had decided in the end. It is also
not as busy as it used to be, taking on about 120 cases this year, 50 or so
less than a generation ago.
Probably its two most important current cases concern the redrawing of
constituency boundaries to improve representation of racial minorities and
the issue of California's system of unitary taxation, opposed by Barclays.
Both have received recent oral hearings prior to definitive written
judgments, usually handed down 3-6 months later.
The public sessions, supplementing mountains of written briefs, are not
necessarily decisive, but more of an opportunity for the justices to strut
their stuff before arguing it out in private. This may be just as well for
Barclays, for the thrust of questioning from the bench was not in its
favour. And the court's word is law.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
