<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Letters to the Editor: EU voting system could look to US
example
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ANDREW G HYDE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Ian Davidson's piece on the latest chapter in the ongoing European
constitutional showdown, this time on majority voting after enlargement
('Vengeance of a Union scorned', April 2/3) recalls the need for the EU to
consider establishing a bicameral legislature.
Such a legislature could be modelled on the American system: designed to
balance the power between large and small states. The interests of larger
countries would be reflected in the existing European parliament, where
individual national voting strength would continue to be determined (within
certain parameters) by population size. For smaller states, there would be
another chamber, a senate, allowing all member states equal representation.
Perhaps the Council of Ministers, still composed of ministers from member
state governments, could evolve into this second chamber.
The creation of such an upper chamber, as was envisaged for the American
system, would ensure a measure of state autonomy in a union beginning to
forge a larger unified identity. In the federalist papers written by
America's founding fathers, they said this about the proposed US Senate: the
'equal vote allowed to each state is at once a constitutional recognition of
the portion of sovereignty remaining in the individual states . . . (The
Senate) will derive its powers from the states as political and coequal
societies . . .' Although it is directly elected now, the US Senate was
originally designed to secure the interests of the state governments against
a powerful centre.
The British government, looking ahead to the 1996 intergovernmental
conference, needs to devise a way of promoting a broader European Union,
while at the same time reserving to itself those elements of its own
sovereignty deemed important.
Andrew G Hyde,
1350 Beverly Road,
Apartment 1208,
McLean,
Virginia 22101, US
</TEXT>
<XX>
