<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Skies without limits: A look at the problems facing airlines
in the former Soviet Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The large blue and green globe advertising Aeroflot on a Moscow avenue used
to boast of the airline's comfort and speed. More recently, the neon-lit
words have been removed, leaving just the globe and the Aeroflot emblem.
The alteration proved symbolic. Two crashes - one last month of an Airbus
operated by the successor to the Aeroflot of Soviet times (which still uses
its name) and another in January of an aircraft run by a tiny offshoot -
have severely damaged the Russian airline industry's image.
The revelation this week that the pilot in the Aeroflot crash, which killed
all 75 people on board, had been teaching his children how to fly confirmed
western suspicions that safety and discipline have fallen to dangerous
levels. The accident has brought home to the Russian government the need to
restructure the country's civil aviation industry and tighten its
supervision.
Since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, Aeroflot has splintered into
not just 15 airlines - one in each newly independent republic - but also
about 300 regional and town-based mini-carriers. The break-up has
exacerbated the problems of the old Aeroflot: ageing aircraft, dilapidated
airports and poor service.
Most of the new companies are state-owned, small and inefficient. In spite
of the break-up of the old monopoly, few compete on the same routes,
reducing incentives to improve standards. And they have little scope for
cross-subsidising unprofitable domestic routes - some of which provide
virtually the only form of transport in Russia's far north and east.
Some help came in January 1992, when state price controls were lifted,
enabling airlines to price their tickets at more realistic levels.
Nevertheless, the Russian pilots' union reckons that last year only half of
the country's airlines - mostly those that inherited profitable routes -
made money.
'We are a country of extremes. We were thrown from the old state monopoly
system right into a market without any rules,' says Mr Alfred Malinovski,
head of the union. 'We interpreted the concept of a market in the most
radical way by breaking up Aeroflot into 300 companies which turned out to
be unmanageable. You can do that sort of thing with a state-owned laundry
monopoly, but not with civil aviation.'
The regulatory machinery is proving particularly ineffective. The old Soviet
civil aviation ministry was replaced by a Russian air transport department
to supervise airlines within Russia, and an inter-state aviation committee
to agree common standards on issues such as safety among the independent
republics. But both have lacked political clout, staff and money.
Breaches of safety rules are highly visible on flights within the former
Soviet Union. Travelling can be an unnerving experience: some passengers
tell tales of heavy luggage being piled up against safety exits, despite
complaints by western travellers; others say that, after their hand luggage
had been carefully weighed at the check-in counters, young traders were
allowed on to the aircraft at the last minute with outsize parcels.
Passengers on the tragic Aeroflot flight to Hong Kong may have seen little
to distinguish the Airbus they were travelling on from those of western
airlines. But Mr Malinovski says a fall in morale and discipline has
affected Russia's domestic and international pilots.
He suggests setting up an independent, properly funded civil aviation
authority, capable of attracting skilled staff and with the authority to
devise and enforce regulations for the industry.
Yet that would not overcome the problems airlines have in making the
investment necessary to improve standards. Mr Mark Jarvis, Moscow
representative of Fleming's, the UK investment bank with interests in
aircraft leasing and manufacturing in Russia, says: 'None of the baby
Aeroflots has any money left for anything else once they've paid for fuel
and maintenance . . . They cannot even afford a new paint job for Dollars
50,000, or to refurbish interiors, let alone acquire new aircraft.'
In large part, the financing problems stem from Aeroflot's disintegration.
There is a need for consolidation, but political upheavals, disagreements
about the direction of market reforms, and preoccupations with other
pressing matters mean the governments of Russia and most of the former
Soviet republics lack a strategy for the industry.
An example of this is Moscow's indecision over Aeroflot-Russian
International Airlines, the full name of the rump of Aeroflot. The
privatisation ministry wants to break the carrier into more than one company
prior to selling shares to the public. But other officials and the airline's
executives want to preserve a unified national flag-carrier, able to compete
against international rivals.
While Aeroflot's successors languish, a bright spot is the emergence of a
few privately funded competitors. The most prominent is Transaero, which
boasts western-style service, by stewardesses trained by Air France, and
five leased Boeings maintained by Israelis.
Created in 1992 with backing from a private Russian bank, it flies to eight
destinations within the former Soviet Union for a small premium over the
prices asked by Aeroflot's heirs operating the same routes. Mr Leonid
Kligerman, Transaero's public relations manager, says: 'For 70 years,
passengers flying Aeroflot did not even know what service meant. We make it
our business to show them. Having flown with us once, they will always fly
with us.'
Transaero's success is due partly to its ability to 'cherry-pick' profitable
routes - with destinations such as the oil town of Nizhnevartovsk and the
holiday resort of Sochi. It is also possibly aided by the fact that the
mother of Transaero's chairman heads the inter-state aviation committee.
Until the Russian authorities inject some coherence into the state sector,
allowing private entrepreneurship to flourish at its expense may be the only
way to provide Russian passengers with a genuine choice. The risk is that
further lives may be lost before necessary changes are made.
</TEXT>
