<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Man in the News: Rough words, smooth player - Umberto Bossi
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Italian politics, battles are usually won without ever being fought.
Politicians posture loudly, muster their weaponry in public but rarely move
to a real confrontation. Instead, behind the smokescreen of belligerent
statements, they measure the strength of their opponents. Then a deal is
struck on the basis of a hypothetical battle.
It is essential to grasp the nature of this phoney warfare to appreciate the
game played out this week by Mr Umberto Bossi, fiery leader of the populist
Lombard League.
Through a mass of contradictory and increasingly belligerent statements, Mr
Bossi has been seeking to extract the maximum price for forming a government
with media magnate Mr Silvio Berlusconi and the neo-fascist MSI/National
Alliance of Mr Gianfranco Fini.
The stakes are high. For the past three years, Mr Bossi and the Northern
League have represented the one genuinely new national force in Italian
politics and have played a vital role in breaking the hold of the
traditional parties. But the sudden appearance and extraordinary electoral
success of fellow northerner Mr Berlusconi and his Forza Italia movement has
threatened to eclipse the League and with it the political career of Mr
Bossi.
Mr Bossi's aim has been to ensure the League retains its identity within the
government likely to be formed by Mr Berlusconi and to prevent the media
mogul from dominating the exercise of power. But behind these strategic
aims, there has been considerable bile.
Mr Bossi finds it hard to stomach the success of Mr Berlusconi whom he
regards as a political parvenu. His political career has been a tough,
lonely 15-year struggle to forge a grassroots protest movement based on the
support of small traders, artisans and blue-collar workers in the industrial
heartland of the north around Milan. His target has been constant:
misgovernment by Rome. It was largely a one-man show based on Mr Bossi's
enormous energy, personal magnetism and his ability to formulate a political
credo in clear terms (often delivered in the coarsest of language).
In contrast, Mr Berlusconi has become a national political leader in less
than four months, riding effortlessly on the back of his huge financial and
media resources. Even the two men's styles of dress are different. Mr
Bossi's clothes are wrinkled, the colours clashing, the tie askew and hair
dishevelled. Mr Berlusconi is carefully manicured, a double-breasted suit
meticulously pressed, the colours matching.
Thus it was not so surprising that at the beginning of this week Mr
Berlusconi was being branded by Mr Bossi as a 'threat to democracy'. By
mid-week, Mr Bossi ever-more garrulous, had dubbed the man likely to form
Italy's next government as Berluskaiser - Berlusconi the Kaiser.
To raise the stakes, Mr Bossi succeeded in injecting a new element into the
phoney war. He gave the impression that he was actually serious when he
threatened to keep the League out of Italy's next government. He also began
to talk of teaming the League with the centre and left parties defeated in
last month's general elections.
Tension increased further when Mr Berlusconi cut off negotiations with Mr
Bossi and threatened - if asked by President Oscar Lugi Scalfaro to form
Italy's next government - to chose whom he pleased. Mr Berlusconi, too, gave
the impression his threat was real.
But by the end of the week, it looked pretty much as though all parties had
assessed each other's weaknesses and strengths. The three main parties that
formed the Freedom Alliance (which won 366 of the 630 seats in the chamber
of deputies) look condemned to forge an agreement to govern Italy.
Mr Bossi was even seen shaking hands with Mr Fini. This was remarkable
considering that Mr Bossi had recently dubbed the neo-fascist leader as a
'political nobody', and that during the election campaign he had said:
'Fascism cannot be allowed into the government. This would open the doors to
Nazis in Germany and Le Pen in France.' Until now Mr Bossi has insisted his
electoral alliance was solely with Mr Berlusconi and Forza Italia.
The kind of compromise Mr Bossi is seeking would be based on a clear
commitment by the next government to bring in constitutional reforms that
would make Italy a more federal state. In return, he would accept both Mr
Berlusconi and Mr Fini's desire to introduce a strong directly-elected
president (such as in France) but with a shorter mandate.
But Mr Bossi can only sell this to his League rank and file, he said in a
newspaper interview yesterday, if 'Berlusconi divests himself of all
interests which are incompatible with holding government office'.
Mr Bossi acknowledged this could be an obstacle. 'This autocrat will have
immense power in his hands: the government, parliament, television,
newspapers, publishing, insurance, mutual funds and store chains. This has
to be monitored . . . The League will do this. It will be the guarantor of
democracy.'
Mr Bossi is right to raise these issues, just as he is to question the
presence in a future Berlusconi-led government of the MSI, given its
unreconstructured fascist wing. But the Lombard leader's political
credibility is undermined by the opportunistic way he took advantage of his
alliance with Mr Berlusconi and Forza Italia to fight the elections.
If the League does not join the government, it risks losing supporters to Mr
Berlusconi. Mr Bossi would then become the head of a querulous regional
party, whose power base was limited to Piedmont, Lombardy and the Veneto. If
the League does join the government, it has to keep itself distinct from
Forza Italia and ensure it is strong enough to outlive the Berlusconi
phenomenon.
It is also a fair bet that Mr Bossi himself will not be part of the
government. He wants to keep his powder dry to snipe from the side-lines,
permanently threatening to pull League support away from Mr Berlusconi. The
next few days will determine whether Mr Bossi will become a serious player
on the national scene or be marginalised to run a vituperative regional
party.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
