<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Leadership poll boosts Heseltine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Heseltine's credentials for the Conservative leadership were
bolstered yesterday when an opinion poll suggested that he was Mr John
Major's nearest challenger to lead the party. One-third of Tory supporters
think he should lead the party into the next general election.
In findings that could further damage Mr Major's leadership prospects, the
MORI poll put him just four points ahead of Mr Heseltine among Tory
supporters - and well behind him when the views of all voters were taken
into account.
But as Mr Major prepared to celebrate the second anniversary of the Tories'
general election victory, the poll dealt a blow to the leadership
aspirations of other potential challengers.
Yesterday's poll, published in London's Evening Standard newspaper,
indicated that only 12 per cent of Tory supporters thought chancellor Mr
Kenneth Clarke, until recently considered the frontrunner to succeed Mr
Major, would best lead the party into the next general election.
Mr Michael Portillo and Mr Michael Howard, regarded as leading challengers
from the right, polled just 4 per cent and 1 per cent respectively - less
than Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, who polled 7 per cent.
Among the public at large, 32 per cent rated Mr Heseltine the best
prospective leader, against just 19 per cent for Mr Major and 11 per cent
for Mr Clarke.
Sir Norman Fowler, Tory party chairman, marked the election anniversary by
publishing a booklet purporting to setting out the government's
achievements.
</TEXT>
