<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Lottery pair lead in vetting stakes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nearly nine weeks into the great National Lottery stakes two of the bidders
appear to have gone into an early lead - at least as far as the volume of
questions they have received from the Office of National Lottery.
The two are Camelot, a consortium that includes De La Rue and Cadbury
Schweppes, and Lotco, an associated company of the Rank Organisation.
They were already widely considered to be front-ranking applicants before
receiving a greater number of vetting questions than other bidders.
Camelot advertised for staff last month and has already had more than 2,000
applicants for about 200 of the more important jobs. It intends to make
conditional appointments before the winner of the lottery is announced.
Most other candidates being vetted have received only a handful of questions
 -typically a mere three or four. Those who have had only a small number of
queries range from Games For Good Causes, the Ladbroke-MAI consortium; the
Great British Lottery Company, which includes Granada and Carlton
Communications; Richard Branson's UK Lottery Foundation; the Rothschild
Tattersalls Lottery Consortium; and Rainbow, a consortium put together by
Sir Patrick Sheehy, the BAT chairman. The position of The Enterprise
Lottery, a consortium including the Tote and Thorn EMI, is unknown.
Camelot is believed to have received several dozen questions and Rank has
also received a significant number of detailed questions.
The eight consortia are vying for the right to run the UK's first national
lottery in modern times - an operation that could turn into the world's
largest single lottery.
The Office of the National Lottery has reached the half-way stage in the
selection process and hopes to announce the winner by the last week of May.
