<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Minister stresses transport shift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Any fresh impetus to encourage private-sector investment in Britain's
transport infrastructure will have to come from companies and banks rather
than government, Mr Roger Freeman, the transport minister, said yesterday.
He said proposals would be considered on a project-by-project basis rather
than by reference to a rigid set of rules. The approach would be deal-driven
to allow flexibility, particularly in the early stages of negotiation and
development.
Mr Freeman's comments, made at a conference on Merseyside, may disappoint
construction companies and other potential private investors in
infrastructure projects which had been looking for a stronger lead from
ministers.
The government had encouraged joint financing of projects with companies by
starting its private-sector initiative, he told the conference.
Companies were 'understandably worried' about investing time, effort and
money in uncertain or ill-defined projects because of 'legislative, planning
and public-policy risks' in the early stages, said Mr Freeman, but he
remained convinced these problems could be solved.
To compensate for these risks the government had agreed to make
contributions to the costs of preparing a bid. In the case of the Channel
tunnel rail link this had worked out at Pounds 1.5m per competing
consortium.
Mr Freeman added that government might agree to dispense with competition
for some projects, provided the private sector produced something
innovative. No two projects were the same: the right solution for the west
coast main railway line might not apply to a new Scottish air traffic
control centre or a new road bridge over the Thames, he said.
</TEXT>
