<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Political turmoil may slow Mexican recovery: Business
confidence is tumbling and interest rates are rising sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prospect of a rapid recovery in Mexico's economy is receding after a
series of blows to business confidence and a sharp rise in domestic interest
rates.
The government has officially forecast growth of 3 per cent this year. But
officials now say that this may be too optimistic. The increase in US
bond-yields, and political turmoil following the peasant uprising in Chiapas
and the murder of presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio, have pushed
up short-term interest rates to over 14 per cent, and are expected to reduce
private-sector investment.
'The recovery expected for the second quarter could now be postponed to the
third quarter,' said one senior government official 'If this (political
uncertainty) goes on for much longer, the consequences could be worse.'
Most private sector economists have recently cut their estimates for growth.
Mr Ernesto Cervera, of the consultancy GEA, says the economy will grow by
about 2 per cent this year, from an earlier estimate of 2.4 per cent. Mr
Rodolfo De la Torre, of the Centre of Analysis and Economic Investigation
has cut his forecast from 4.1 per cent to 3.5 per cent, and says he may
reduce it further.
The expectation of low growth has contributed to a 25 per cent fall in the
Mexican stock market, from its high of early February, as analysts have cut
estimates for earnings of leading companies. The decline has forced some
companies to put off equity offerings, due to finance investment.
A weak economy could spell trouble for Mexico's governing party, which faces
presidential elections this August. Last year Mexico's economy expanded by
just 0.4 per cent, and in the final two quarters growth was negative.
Opposition to government policies has grown as unemployment has increased,
and business profits have fallen.
The slowdown has caused a shift in government thinking on economic policy in
the recognition that obstacles to growth and inefficiencies in the economy
are greater than once thought. The campaign platform of the governing party
puts much greater stress on industrial policy, legal reform, employment
generation and income redistribution than has the administration of
President Carlos Salinas.
The government expected a significant pick-up in economic growth this year
based on an increase in public spending and expansion in private sector
investment. Last year private investment all but dried up, largely because
of high real interest rates, uncertainty that prevailed over the fate of the
North American Free Trade Agreement, and the unwillingness of many banks to
lend money because of problems with non-performing loans.
But the uncertainty over the North American Free Trade Agreement has been
replaced by concern over the electoral and political process this year. The
uprising in Chiapas followed by the assassination of Mr Colosio has left
some wondering whether Mexico is facing a period of sustained political
upheaval, which could affect the business and economic climate.
Such fears seem to have increased after the government's special
investigator concluded that seven people conspired to kill Mr Colosio,
including an official from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party in
charge of security at the rally at which the candidate was killed.
Speculation over who ordered Mr Colosio's death has over-shadowed the
campaign of the PRI's new presidential candidate, Mr Ernesto Zedillo.
The political uncertainty has coincided with higher US bond yields, which
have made Mexican debt instrument less attractive to foreign investors. Both
events have forced up Mexican interest rates. In this week's auction
short-term rates on 28-day paper rose to 14.31 per cent, compared to 8.81
per cent in late February. Inflation is expected to fall under 7 per cent
this year.
Mexico is particularly vulnerable to perceptions of political risk and high
US interest rates because of its need to finance a current account deficit
that last year reached Dollars 23.4bn, and is expected to be still more this
year. The government is formally committed to a stable exchange rate, and
therefore cannot increase trade competitiveness through a one-off
devaluation.
The administration nevertheless argues that once the uncertainty is
resolved, prospects for growth are high. In its annual report, the Central
Bank points to buoyant exports, the steady rise in manufacturing and sound
public finances as reasons for optimism. Such a view may turn out to be
correct. But after waiting more than five years for the fruits of pro-market
economic reforms of President Salinas, many Mexicans are becoming impatient.
</TEXT>
<XX>
