<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Yeltsin spokesman flies G7 kite
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Boris Yeltsin's spokesman, who has been known to announce foreign
policy initiatives that are subsequently dismissed by the government,
yesterday suggested linking Russia's joining Nato's Partnership for Peace
with its admission to the Group of Seven.
Mr Vyacheslav Kostikov said he believed the military co-operation foreseen
by Nato's partnership plan might be difficult without closer economic
co-ordination between Russia and the world's seven richest industrialised
nations.
'How can we talk about such co-operation, abstracting ourselves from
economic co-operation?' he said. 'You know that Russia wants to join G7. Why
shouldn't these two problems be linked? If we are invited to co-operate in
political and military spheres, why shouldn't this be expanded to economic
co-operation?'
The G7 countries, all Nato members except Japan, have invited Kremlin chiefs
to their summits in the last few years, but have stopped short of expanding
G7 to include Russia.
However, Mr Kostikov's demand that Russia be given G7 status appeared more
of an effort to impress domestic opinion than a practical proposal.
Mr Sergei Karaganov, a foreign policy expert and member of the president's
advisory council, expressed surprise at Mr Kostikov's declaration. 'I do not
believe that could be the official position of any relevant ministry or of
the president's administration,' he said.
Only a few weeks ago Mr Kostikov said that Russia might take six or seven
months to sign up for Partnership for Peace, thereby risking embarrassing
isolation as the odd man out after its neighbours had joined. But that
statement has since been dismissed by the Foreign Ministry, which has
suggested that Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the foreign minister, might sign as early
as April 21.
Mr Karaganov said that on that occasion Mr Kostikov had been trying, on his
own initiative, to protect the Kremlin from possible new attacks from the
conservative state Duma, which would use the Nato agreement as an excuse to
denounce the president and the government.
In a similar vein, Mr Kostikov yesterday suggested that the Partnership for
Peace might not be signed by Mr Kozyrev, but by a lower-ranking official.
</TEXT>
