<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Peace envoys step up Bosnia drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff and AP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
American and Russian negotiators yesterday stepped up pressure on Serbs and
Moslems to end two years of war in Bosnia as heavy fighting raged over a
strategic point south of the Gorazde enclave.
Mr Charles Redman, US envoy and one of the architects of last month's
landmark federation agreement between Croats and Moslems, arrived in
Sarajevo to throw his weight behind the peace-making efforts of Gen Sir
Michael Rose, the UN commander.
He stressed that he had come to discuss an overall political settlement, not
just a ceasefire deal. The Moslems have been reluctant to endorse a
ceasefire for fear of consolidating Serb gains.
Mr Redman said after meeting Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic: 'We have
some ideas. We're are talking about them but it will, no doubt, take a few
days to sort these out.'
Mr Vitaly Churkin, the Russian negotiator, is due in Belgrade tomorrow,
where he is expected to put pressure on the Serbs to agree a deal even at
the cost of some territorial concessions.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, which has given more
detailed reports of the bloodshed than the UN military command, said its
representatives in Gorazde could hear 'very loud impacts' from artillery to
the south.
This would suggest a fight for control of the village of Vitkovici, where a
munitions factory is thought to be located. If the Serbs capture it they
will have moved closer to clearing a route between Serbia and eastern
Bosnia, a long-standing ambition.
A Serb commander claimed that his side was close to seizing the whole
enclave, one of three so-called safe areas for Moslems designated by the UN.
'Soon we shall occupy the entire region of Gorazde and thus gain control
over both banks of the Drina (river),' said Gen Vlado Spremo, Bosnian
commander.
Mr Kris Janowski, a UNHCR spokesman, said that as of yesterday morning, 83
people had been killed and 376 wounded in fighting around Gorazde, including
16 deaths in the past 24 hours. A ceasefire proclaimed by the Moslems on
Thursday night appears to have brought no more than a temporary lull in
fighting.
Opposition politicians demanded a no-confidence vote on Croatia's defence
minister following an arms warehouse explosion that sent shrapnel flying up
to three miles away and left five soldiers missing, AP reports.
But members of President Franjo Tudjman's ruling party charged that the move
was unconnected to Thursday's blast and merely another ploy to oust
right-wing Defence Minister Gojko Susak.
</TEXT>
