<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / US frustrated by failed promise of trade reform:
Washington's hopes are being pinned on Ichiro Ozawa and his commitment to
institutional change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton's public 'regret' yesterday at the resignation of Mr
Morihiro Hosokawa as Japanese prime minister could not disguise the
increasing US frustration at the virtual paralysis of his government.
The US trade negotiating strategy with Japan had been predicated on the
belief that Mr Hosokawa was a reformer, keen to take on those Japanese
bureaucrats seen in Washington as the stumbling block to greater access for
US goods and services.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, and other officials consistently
maintained that US pressure on Japan was designed to reinforce, not
undermine, a premier whose domestic popularity had been remarkably high by
recent Japanese standards.
Even the most recent ratcheting up of this pressure, with the naming of
Japan as an unfair trader under the terms of the revived Super 301 trade
process, was seen in Washington as a means of giving Mr Hosokawa's
government more time to respond.
Although Japan came up with a plan to give Motorola of the US greater
opportunities in the cellular phone market, other Japanese policies,
including a budget stimulus, have been stalled.
Over time this frustration has more than offset the reasonable personal
rapport between the two leaders, both previously provincial governors. Even
after their abortive summit in February, which failed to resolve outstanding
trade differences, Mr Clinton entertained Mr Hosokawa for a social breakfast
at the White House.
But even as they ate, US officials were investigating political alternatives
in Tokyo. Mr Tsutomu Hata, the foreign minister and a possible successor to
Mr Hosokawa, has become reasonably well known in Washington, but without
ever transcending the barrier of being just another fungible Japanese
politician whose interests are principally domestic.
Increasingly, hopes have been pinned on Mr Ichiro Ozawa, the former LDP
cabinet member and now the political power, such as it is, in the Hosokawa
cabinet, as a man who could get things done behind the scenes.
Much as Mr Hosokawa's brief memoirs before he became prime minister became
useful reading in Washington, so has Mr Ozawa's recent publication -
Blueprint for Building a New Japan. Washington understands that Mr Ozawa has
political problems of his own in Japan but his commitment to domestic
institutional reform and a strong US relationship is considered an advantage
and it is hoped he remains in a position of influence in the new government.
One senior White House policy-maker was recently asked if he was worried
about Mr Ozawa's scandal-tainted reputation as the 'Richard Nixon of Japan'.
He replied: 'What's wrong with that?'
</TEXT>
