<HEADLINE>
FT  09 APR 94 / Public rues a lost chance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese public, like a kabuki audience moved by a familiar plot, found
their disappointment at Mr Morihiro Hosokawa's resignation yesterday
tempered by a sense of the inevitable.
'It is regrettable,' said one man in Kumamoto, Mr Hosokawa's home
prefecture. 'But it can't be helped since, for a prime minister, integrity
is crucial.'
To a public that had become accustomed to the whims of their leader, the
sudden change of mind by Mr Hosokawa, who had spent a good part of the week
denying he would resign, appeared perfectly in character.
Mr Hosokawa's approach to government, criticised by his enemies as
lightweight and irresponsible, still had its fans. Many citizens could not
hide their regret; they had hoped he would change not just the substance of
Japanese politics but its style as well.
'It is very disappointing,' said Mr Eiji Hirabayashi, a businessman in
Tokyo. 'His policies were good, his image was good and, compared with his
predecessors, he was relatively clean.'
There was also sympathy for the man whose public rating, even in the midst
of scandal, remained high. But that popularity could not help Mr Hosokawa
overcome his inability to run the country. 'As a person he is good, but I
would have preferred a more effective leader,' Mr Hirabayashi said.
Business leaders were more scathing. Many vented their frustration and
criticism not at Mr Hosokawa alone but at the entire government.
'It is imperative that the government gets its act together to prevent any
further delay in the critical areas of deregulation and economic stimulus,'
Mr Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman of Toyota, said.
'We can only (insist) that the Japanese government quickly composes itself
and starts acting to address responsibly the needs of the country and the
international community during this crucial period.'
Many people nevertheless give Mr Hosokawa credit for starting to address
those very needs. Tainted though he was by the shadow of scandal, the
youthful prime minister photographed walking with US President Bill Clinton
during last year's Apec conference in Seattle is likely to be remembered as
the man who initiated much-needed change in Japan.
</TEXT>
<XX>
