FT  08 APR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Aluminium finds support -
Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALUMINIUM prices rose to session highs in after hours 'kerb' trading at the
London Metal Exchange, erasing earlier losses and positioning themselves for
a further rally, dealers said.
Overnight investment fund selling left the market looking vulnerable at
Dollars 1,290 a tonne for three months delivery. But 'there was good support
at the lows,' said one trader, 'and this close (Dollars 1,300.50 a tonne,
down Dollars 11.25) takes us back into the Dollars 1,300-Dollars 1,320 band
again, with a good chance of taking out those highs.'
COPPER also recovered from its morning lows, but the three months price
still closed Dollars 17 down at Dollars 1,876 a tonne, the lowest for five
weeks.
LEAD prices rallied smartly from four-month lows, with the market's
fundamentals not really justifying sharp declines, while selling below
Dollars 450 lacked follow-through.
Compiled from Reuter
