<HEADLINE>
FT  08 APR 94 / International Company News: Dow Jones posts advance of 30%
in first period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Dow Jones, the media group which publishes the Wall Street Journal,
yesterday reported a 30 per cent rise in first quarter net income, helped by
sharply improved operating earnings at all of its three divisions.
The group reported net income of Dollars 40.17m, or 40 cents a share,
compared with Dollars 30.95m, or 31 cents, in the same period of last year.
Revenues rose 7.7 per cent to Dollars 499.2m from Dollars 463.4m.
The figures included a Dollars 3m one-time after-tax charge from the
adoption of a new accounting standard relating to employees' post-employment
benefits. Excluding this, net income was up 39.5 per cent, the company
reported.
Consolidated operating income was 35.8 per cent higher than in the same
period of last year, at Dollars 88.75m.
The information services segment, which includes the Dow Jones/Telerate and
business information services operations, saw operating income rise 39.7 per
cent to Dollars 48.14m on revenues 10 per cent higher at Dollars 230m.
Business publications had operating income of Dollars 41.5m, up 30.5 per
cent, on revenues 7.2 per cent higher at Dollars 213.5m. The Wall Street
Journal's advertising lineage rose 1.7 per cent, but on a per issue basis
was even with a year earlier.
Ottaway Newspapers, the group's community newspaper subsidiary, reported a
17.8 per cent rise in operating income to Dollars 4.43m, on revenues 1.3 per
cent higher at Dollars 55.78m. Advertising lineage fell 1.1 per cent.
The company's shares closed Dollars 1 1/4 higher on the New York Stock
Exchange, at Dollars 39 1/8.
</TEXT>
